# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen received royal burgh status from David I of Scotland (1124–1153), which transformed the city economically.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The traditional industries of fishing, paper-making, shipbuilding, and textiles have been overtaken by the oil industry and Aberdeen's seaport.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Heliport is one of the busiest commercial heliports in the world, and the seaport is the largest in the north-east part of Scotland.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] A university town, the city is known for the University of Aberdeen, founded in 1495 as King's College, the fifth oldest university in the English-speaking world and located in Old Aberdeen.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] During the mid-18th to mid-20th centuries, Aberdeen's buildings incorporated locally quarried grey granite, which may sparkle like silver because of its high mica content.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Since the discovery of North Sea oil in 1969, Aberdeen has been known as the offshore **oil capital of Europe**.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Based upon the discovery of prehistoric villages around the mouths of the rivers Dee and Don, the area around Aberdeen is thought to have been settled for at least 6,000 years.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The name given to Aberdeen translates as 'mouth of the river Don', and is recorded as Aberdon in 1172 and Aberden in c.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The first element of the name is the Pictish word *aber* 'river mouth'.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The second element is from the Celtic river goddess Devona.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is usually described as within the historical Pictish territory and became Gaelic-speaking at some time in the medieval period.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Old Aberdeen is the approximate location of Aberdon, the first settlement of Aberdeen; this literally means "the mouth of the Don".
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The Celtic word *aber* means "river mouth", as in modern Welsh (Aberystwyth, Aberdare, Aberbeeg etc.).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Gaelic name is *Obar Dheathain* (variation: *Obairreadhain*; **obar* presumably being a loan from the earlier Pictish; the Gaelic term is *inbhir*), and in Latin, the Romans referred to the river as *Devana*.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Medieval (or Ecclesiastical) Latin has it as *Aberdonia*.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The local Doric pronunciation, [ˌeːbərˈdin] ⓘ or [ˈeːbərdin] ⓘ (with a long *ay* sound), is frequently rendered *Aiberdeen* or *Aiberdein*.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen area has seen human settlement for at least 8,000 years.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The city began as two separate burghs: Old Aberdeen at the mouth of the river Don; and New Aberdeen, a fishing and trading settlement, where the Denburn waterway entered the river Dee estuary.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The earliest charter was granted by William the Lion in 1179 and confirmed the corporate rights granted by David I.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] In 1214, Aberdeen Burgesses were granted a Royal Charter by Alexander II of Scotland giving them the sole right to form a Guild.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] This body exercised power in the composition of the local council, and the affairs of the town.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The Burgesses of the Guild were an integral part of the council for more than 700 years and played a considerable role in the growth and development of Aberdeen.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] In 1319, the Great Charter of Robert the Bruce transformed Aberdeen into a property-owning and financially independent community.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Granted with it was the nearby Forest of Stocket, whose income formed the basis for the city's Common Good Fund which still benefits Aberdonians.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of Scottish Independence, Aberdeen was under English rule, so Robert the Bruce laid siege to Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308, followed by executing the English garrison.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The city was burned by Edward III of England in 1336, but was rebuilt and extended.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The city was strongly fortified to prevent attacks by neighbouring lords, but the gates were removed by 1770.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's medieval council registers survive from 1398 onwards and are exceptional for their quantity and continuity among surviving Scottish burgh records.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The earliest eight volumes, from 1398 to 1511, have been included in the UNESCO UK Memory of the World Register, and have been edited in a digital edition.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of the Three Kingdoms of 1644 to 1647 the city was plundered by both sides.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] In 1644, it was taken and ransacked by Royalist troops after the Battle of Aberdeen and two years later it was stormed by a Royalist force under the command of the George Gordon, 2nd Marquess of Huntly.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] An outbreak of bubonic plague over 1687 and 1688 killed 8.5% of the population, adding to the economic and demographic damage caused by war.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] In the 18th century, a new Town Hall was built and the first social services appeared with the Aberdeen Infirmary at Woolmanhill in 1739 and the Aberdeen Lunatic Asylum in 1800.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The expensive infrastructure works led to the city becoming bankrupt in 1817 during the Post-Napoleonic depression, an economic downturn immediately after the Napoleonic Wars; but the city's prosperity later recovered.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The increasing economic importance of Aberdeen and the development of the shipbuilding and fishing industries led to the construction of the present harbour including Victoria Dock and the South Breakwater, and the extension of the North Pier.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Gas street lighting arrived in 1824 and an enhanced water supply appeared in 1830 when water was pumped from the Dee to a reservoir in Union Place.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] An underground sewer system replaced open sewers in 1865.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The city absorbed the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee in 1891.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Over the course of World War II Aberdeen was attacked 32 times by the German Luftwaffe.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] One of the most devastating attacks was on Wednesday 21 April 1943 when 29 Luftwaffe Dornier 217s flying from Stavanger, Norway attacked the city between the hours of 22:17 and 23:04.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] A total of 98 civilians and 27 servicemen were killed, along with 12,000 houses damaged, after a mixture of 127 Incendiary, High Explosive and Cluster bombs were dropped on the city in one night.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Two books written in 2018 and 2022 using bombing records held in London identified that unexploded bombs from the 1943 raid were found in the 1950s and 1980s making the bombs dropped 129 in total.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Damage from the raid can still be seen in some parts of Aberdeen.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The arms and banner of the city show three silver towers on red.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] This motif dates from at least the time of Robert the Bruce and represents the buildings that stood on the three hills of medieval Aberdeen: Aberdeen Castle on Castle Hill (today's Castlegate); the city gate on Port Hill; and a church on St Catherine's Hill (now levelled).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] "Bon Accord" is the motto of the city and is French for "Good Agreement".
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Legend tells that its use dates from a password used by Robert the Bruce during the 14th century Wars of Scottish Independence, when he and his men laid siege to the English-held Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] It is still widely present in the city, throughout street names, business names and the city's Bon Accord shopping mall.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The shield in the coat of arms is supported by two leopards.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] A local magazine is called the "Leopard" and, when Union Bridge was widened in the 20th century, small statues of the creature in a sitting position were cast and placed on top of the railing posts (known locally as Kelly's Cats).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The city's toast is "Happy to meet, sorry to part, happy to meet again".
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] In 2012, HSBC named Aberdeen as a leading business hub and one of eight 'super cities' spearheading the UK's economy, marking it as the only city in Scotland so designated.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] In 2018, Aberdeen was found to be the best city in the UK to start a business in a study released by card payment firm Paymentsense.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen City is one of 32 council areas of Scotland, administered by Aberdeen City Council.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The council meets at Aberdeen Town House and has its main offices in the adjoining Marischal College.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The civic head and chair of the council is the Lord Provost.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The council area is also divided into 30 community council areas, 29 of which had community councils operating as at August 2024.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The first burgh of Aberdeen, covering just the New Aberdeen area near the mouth of the Dee, was created by David I (reigned 1124–1153).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Neighbouring Old Aberdeen to the north was subsequently made a separate burgh in 1489.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The burgh of Aberdeen was governed by a corporation, also known as the town council.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] As Aberdeen grew, the council's powers were inadequate to cater for the needs of the growing urban area.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] A separate police commission was established in 1795 with powers to levy taxes and provide infrastructure ('police' in this context being its older meaning of civic government rather than law enforcement).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The first police commission was short-lived, but it was resurrected in 1818 after the town council went bankrupt in 1817.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] From 1818 until 1871 there was a dual system of local government, with the town council and police commission having different roles in Aberdeen's administration.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The police commission was eventually abolished in 1871 and its functions absorbed by the town council.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] In 1891 the city boundaries were significantly enlarged, absorbing the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside, plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The act of parliament which expanded the burgh also confirmed that Aberdeen was entitled to be called a city; it had commonly been described as a city prior to that, but (like most Scottish cities) without official recognition.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Following the absorption of Torry in 1891, the city boundaries straddled the counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was made a county of itself in 1899.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] In 1975 the burgh was replaced by the larger City of Aberdeen district within the Grampian region.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Further local government reforms in 1996 replaced the districts and regions created in 1975 with council areas; the pre-1996 City of Aberdeen district became the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] In the Scottish Parliament, the city is represented by three constituencies with different boundaries: Aberdeen Central and Aberdeen Donside are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Deeside and North Kincardine includes the North Kincardine ward of Aberdeenshire Council.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] A further seven MSPs are elected as part of the North East Scotland electoral region.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] In the European Parliament the city was represented by six MEPs as part of the all-inclusive Scotland constituency.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is represented in the Parliament of the United Kingdom by two constituencies, Aberdeen North and Aberdeen South, which are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Being situated between two river mouths, the city has little natural exposure of bedrock.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The small amount of geophysics done, and occasional building-related exposures, combined with small exposures in the banks of the River Don, suggest that it is actually sited on an inlier of Devonian "Old Red" sandstones and silts.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The city extends to 186 km2 (72 sq mi), and includes the former burghs of Old Aberdeen, New Aberdeen, Woodside and the Torry area to the south of River Dee.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] In 2024, this gave the city a population density of 1,249 inhabitants per square kilometre (3,230/sq mi).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The city is built on many hills, with the original beginnings of the city growing from Castle Hill, St.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] When compared to mainland Europe, Aberdeen is further north than almost all of Denmark and plenty of southern Sweden, being just south of Gothenburg in terms of latitude.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen features an oceanic climate (Köppen *Cfb*), with far milder winter temperatures than one might expect for its northern location.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] However, statistically speaking, it is still the coldest city in the UK.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] During the winter, especially throughout December, the length of the day is very short, averaging 6 hours and 41 minutes between sunrise and sunset at the winter solstice.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] As winter progresses, the length of the day grows fairly quickly, to 8 hours and 20 minutes by the end of January.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Around summer solstice, the days will be around 18 hours long, having 17 hours and 55 minutes between sunrise and sunset.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] During this time of the year marginal nautical twilight lasts the entire night.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Temperatures at this time of year hover around 17.0 °C (62.6 °F) during the day in most of the urban area, though nearer 16.0 °C (60.8 °F) directly on the coast, and around 18.0 to 19.0 °C (64.4 to 66.2 °F) in the westernmost suburbs.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Two weather stations collect climate data for the area, Aberdeen/Dyce Airport, and Craibstone.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Both are about 4+1⁄2 miles (7 km) to the northwest of the city centre, and given that they are in close proximity to each other, exhibit very similar climatic regimes.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Dyce tends to have marginally warmer daytime temperatures year-round owing to its slightly lower elevation, though it is more susceptible to harsh frosts.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The coldest temperature to occur in recent years was −16.8 °C (1.8 °F) during December 2010, while the following winter, Dyce set a new February high-temperature station record on 28 February 2012 of 17.2 °C (63.0 °F), and a new March high temperature record of 21.6 °C (70.9 °F) on 25 March 2012.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The average temperature of the sea ranges from 6.6 °C (43.9 °F) in March to 13.8 °C (56.8 °F) in August.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen locality population estimate is 198,590 (2020).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] For the wider settlement of Aberdeen including Cove Bay and Dyce, the population estimate is 220,690 (2020).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] For Aberdeen City council area, the population estimate is 231,780 (2024).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] In 1396, the population was about 3,000.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The 2011 census showed fewer young people in Aberdeen, with 16.4% under 16, as opposed to the national average of 19.2%.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] According to the 2011 census Aberdeen is 91.9% white, ethnically, 24.7% were born outside Scotland, higher than the national average of 16%.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Of this population, 7.6% were born in other parts of the UK.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] 8.2% of Aberdonians stated to be from an ethnic minority (non-white) in the 2011 census, with 9,519 (4.3%) being Asian, with 3,385 (1.5%) coming from India and 2,187 (1.0%) being Chinese.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The city has around 5,610 (2.6%) residents of African or Caribbean origin, which is a higher percentage than both Glasgow and Edinburgh.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] In the household, there were 97,013 individual dwellings recorded in the city, of which 61% were privately owned, 9% privately rented and 23% rented from the council.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The most popular type of dwellings are apartments which comprise 49% of residences followed by semi-detached at just below 22%.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The median income of a household in the city is £16,813 (the mean income is £20,292) (2005) which places approximately 18% households in the city below the poverty line (defined as 60% of the mean income).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Conversely, an Aberdeen postcode has the second highest number of millionaires of any postcode in the UK.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The proportion of people residing in Aberdeen born outside the UK was 21.1% in 2022, compared with 15.9% in 2011 and 6.3% in 2001.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Below are the fifteen largest overseas-born groups in Aberdeen according to the 2022 census, alongside the two previous censuses.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Christianity is the main religion practised in the city.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's largest denominations are the Church of Scotland (through the Presbytery of Aberdeen) and the Roman Catholic Church, both with numerous churches across the city, with the Scottish Episcopal Church having the third-largest number.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The census in 2022 showed that Aberdeen has the highest proportion of non-religious residents of any city in Scotland, with 58% of citizens claiming to have no religion.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] In the Middle Ages, the Kirk of St Nicholas was the only burgh kirk and one of Scotland's largest parish churches.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Like a number of other Scottish kirks, it was subdivided after the Reformation, in this case into the East and West churches.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] At that time, the city also was home to houses of the Carmelites (Whitefriars) and Franciscans (Greyfriars).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The latter survives in modified form as the chapel of Marischal College.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] St Machar's Cathedral was built twenty years after David I (1124–1153) transferred the pre-Reformation diocese from Mortlach in Banffshire to Old Aberdeen in 1137.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Except the episcopate of William Elphinstone (1484–1511), building progressed slowly.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Gavin Dunbar, who followed him in 1518, completed the structure by adding the two western spires and the southern transept.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] It is now a congregation of the Church of Scotland.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Mary's Cathedral is a Roman Catholic cathedral in Gothic style, erected in 1859.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Andrew's Cathedral serves the Scottish Episcopal Church.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] It was constructed in 1817 as Archibald Simpson's first commission and contains a memorial to the consecration of the first bishop of the Episcopal Church in the United States of America, which took place nearby.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] In 1804, St Peter's Church, the first permanent Roman Catholic church in the city after the Reformation was built.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Numerous other Protestant denominations have a presence in Aberdeen.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The Salvation Army citadel on the Castlegate dominates the view of the east end of Union Street.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there is a Unitarian church, established in 1833 and located in Skene Terrace.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Christadelphians have been present in Aberdeen since at least 1844.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Over the years, they have rented space to meet at a number of locations and currently meet in the Inchgarth Community Centre in Garthdee.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Quaker meetinghouse on Crown Street, the only purpose built Friends meeting house in Scotland that is still in use today.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there are a number of Baptist congregations in the city, and Evangelical congregations have been appearing in significant numbers since the late 2000s.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The city also has two meeting houses of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (LDS Church).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] There are also four mosques in Aberdeen which serve the Islamic community in the city.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] There is an Orthodox Jewish Synagogue established in 1945.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Thai Buddhist temple located in the Hazelhead area of the city.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] There are no formal Hindu buildings, although there is a fortnightly Hindu religious gathering on the first and third Sunday afternoons at Queens Cross Parish church hall.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen has a small Baháʼí society.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,756 residents aged three and over, 76,650 (35.2%) considered themselves able to speak or read the Scots language.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,760 residents aged three and over, 2,919 (1.3%) considered themselves able to speak or read Gaelic.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Traditionally, Aberdeen was home to fishing, textile mills, shipbuilding and paper-making.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] These industries have been largely replaced.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] High technology developments in the electronics design and development industry, research in agriculture and fishing and the oil industry, which have been largely responsible for Aberdeen's economic growth, are now major parts of Aberdeen's economy.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Until the 1970s, most of Aberdeen's leading industries dated from the 18th century; mainly these were textiles, foundry work, shipbuilding and paper-making, the oldest industry in the city, with paper having been first made there in 1694.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Paper-making has reduced in importance since the closures of Donside Paper Mill in 2001 and the Davidson Mill in 2005 leaving the Stoneywood Paper Mill with a workforce of approximately 500.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Textile production ended in 2004 when Richards of Aberdeen closed.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Grey granite was quarried at Rubislaw quarry for more than 300 years, and used for paving setts, kerb and building stones, and monumental and other ornamental pieces.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen granite was used to build the terraces of the Houses of Parliament and Waterloo Bridge in London.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The current owners have begun pumping 40 years of rainwater from the quarry to develop a heritage centre on the site.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] In-shore fishing was once the predominant industry but was surpassed by deep-sea fisheries, which derived a great impetus from improved technologies throughout the 20th century.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Catches have fallen because of overfishing and the use of the harbour by oil support vessels, and so although still an important fishing port it is now eclipsed by the more northerly ports of Peterhead and Fraserburgh.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The Fisheries Research Services are headquartered in Aberdeen, and there is a marine research laboratory there.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is well regarded for the agricultural and soil research carried out at The James Hutton Institute (formerly the Macaulay Land Use Research Institute), which has close links to the city's two universities.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The Rowett Research Institute is a world-renowned research centre for studies into food and nutrition located in Aberdeen.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] It has produced three Nobel laureates and there is a high concentration of life scientists working in the city.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] As oil reserves in the North Sea decrease, there is an effort to rebrand Aberdeen as the **energy capital of Europe** rather than the oil capital, and there is interest in the development of new energy sources, and technology transfer from oil into renewable energy and other industries is underway.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The "Energetica" initiative led by Scottish Enterprise has been designed to accelerate this process.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has become a major world centre for undersea petroleum technology.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen had been a major maritime centre throughout the 19th century, when a group of local entrepreneurs launched the first steam-powered trawler.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The steam trawling industry expanded and by 1933 Aberdeen was Scotland's top fishing port, employing nearly 3,000 men with 300 vessels sailing from its harbour.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] By the time oil was coming on stream, much of the trawling fleet had relocated to Peterhead.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Geologists had speculated about oil and gas in the North Sea since the middle of the 20th century, but tapping its deep and inhospitable waters was another story.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] With the Middle Eastern oil sheiks becoming more aware of the political and economic power of their oil reserves and government threats of rationing, the industry began to consider the North Sea as a viable source of oil.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Exploration commenced in the 1960s and the first major find in the British sector was in November 1970 in the Forties field, 110 miles (180 km) east of Aberdeen.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] By late 1975, after years of intense construction, the necessary infrastructure was in place.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Oil flowed through the Forties pipeline system directly to the refinery at far-away Grangemouth.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] In 2011, the Centre for Cities named Aberdeen as the best-placed city for growth in Britain, as the country looked to emerge from the recent economic downturn.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] With energy still providing the backbone of the local economy, recent years have seen very large new investment in the North Sea owing to rising oil prices and favourable government tax incentives.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] This has led to several oil majors and independents building new global offices in the city.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Five of Scotland's top ten businesses are based in Aberdeen with a collective turnover of £14 billion, yielding a profit in excess of £2.4 billion.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Alongside this 29 of Scotland's top 100 businesses are located in Aberdeen with an employment rate of 77.9%, making it the second highest UK city for employment.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Figures released in 2016 ranked Aberdeen as having the second highest number of patents processed per person in the UK.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The traditional shopping streets are Union Street and George Street, now complemented by shopping centres, including the Bon Accord Centre and the Trinity Shopping Centre.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] A £190 million retail development, Union Square, reached completion in late September/early October 2009.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Major retail parks away from the city centre include the Berryden Retail Park, the Kittybrewster Retail Park and the Beach Boulevard Retail Park.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Market has been rebuilt twice, but closed in 2020.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] In March 2004, Aberdeen was awarded Fairtrade City status by the Fairtrade Foundation.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's architecture is known for its principal use during the Victorian era of granite, which has led to its local nickname of the Granite City.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] In Castle Street, a continuation eastwards of Union Street, is the new Aberdeen Town House, a very prominent landmark in Aberdeen, built between 1868 and 1873 to a design by Peddie and Kinnear.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Alexander Marshall Mackenzie's extension to Marischal College on Broad Street, opened by King Edward VII in 1906, created the second largest granite building in the world (after the Escorial, Madrid).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has long been famous for its 45 parks and gardens, and citywide floral displays which include two million roses, eleven million daffodils and three million crocuses.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The city has won the Royal Horticultural Society's Britain in Bloom 'Best City' award ten times, the overall Scotland in Bloom competition twenty times and the large city category every year since 1968.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] However, despite recent spurious reports, Aberdeen has never been banned from the Britain in Bloom competition.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The city won the 2006 Scotland in Bloom "Best City" award along with the International Cities in Bloom award.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The suburb of Dyce also won the Small Towns award.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Duthie Park opened in 1883 on the north bank of the River Dee.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] It was named after and given to the city by Miss Elizabeth Crombie Duthie of Ruthrieston in 1881.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Hazlehead Park, is large and forested, and located on the outskirts of the city.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Johnston Gardens is a small park of one hectare in the west end of the city.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] In 2002, the garden was named the best garden in the British Islands.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Seaton Park, formerly the grounds of a private house, is on the edge of the grounds of St Machar's Cathedral and was acquired for the city in 1947.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has hosted several theatres throughout its history, some of which have been converted or destroyed.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Today, all railway services to the south run via Dundee.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The faster main line from Aberdeen to Perth via Forfar and Strathmore closed in 1967, as a result of the Beeching cuts; the faster main line from Perth to Edinburgh via Glenfarg also closed subsequently in 1970.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] A second station, at Dyce, serves the north of the city centre; it is on the Aberdeen–Inverness line.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] First Aberdeen operates the majority of city bus services, as the successor to Grampian Regional Transport (GRT) and Aberdeen Corporation Tramways.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Secondary operators include Stagecoach Bluebird and Stagecoach South Scotland.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is the global headquarters of parent company FirstGroup, having grown from the GRT Group.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] First is still based at the former Aberdeen Tramways depot on King Street, which has now been redeveloped into a new headquarters and bus depot.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] On 18 April 2025, the "Aberdeen Adventurer" tour bus scheme ran by McGill's Bus Services was launched with 10 stops around the city on a 75-minute loop.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Stops include King's College, Pittodrie Stadium and the Aberdeen Art Gallery with the service due to end on 20 September 2026.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen International Airport (ABZ), sited in Dyce in the north of the city, serves domestic and international destinations in France, the Netherlands, Spain, Ireland and Scandinavian countries.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The heliport, which serves the oil industry and rescue services, is one of the world's busiest commercial heliports.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is connected to the UK's National Cycle Network; it has a track to the south, connecting to cities including Dundee and Edinburgh, and one to the north that forks about 10 miles (15 km) from the city into two different tracks heading to Inverness and Fraserburgh respectively.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Two popular shared-use paths, along old railway lines, are the Deeside Way to Banchory (which will eventually connect to Ballater) and the Formartine and Buchan Way to Ellon, both used by a mixture of cyclists, walkers and occasionally horses.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] In May 2026, a self-service e-bike hire scheme was introduced in Aberdeen, operated by Voi Technology.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Some 350 bikes are available on a pay-as-you-go basis.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The scheme replaced an earlier bike hire scheme which was operated between 2022 and 2024 by *The Big Issue* and Sharebike but which was scrapped because of funding issues as well as vandalism.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Harbour is important as the largest in the north of Scotland and serves the ferry route to Orkney and Shetland.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Established in 1136, the harbour has been referred to as the "oldest business in Britain".
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The Dee Estuary, Aberdeen's harbour, started out as a fishing port, moving on to steam trawlers and serving the oil industry; it is now a major port of departure for the Baltic and Scandinavia.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has two universities, the ancient University of Aberdeen, and Robert Gordon University, a modern university often referred to as RGU.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has a high proportion of students of 11.5%, higher than the national average of 7%.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen began as King's College, Aberdeen, which was founded in 1495 by William Elphinstone (1431–1514), Bishop of Aberdeen and Chancellor of Scotland.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Marischal College, a separate institution, was founded in New Aberdeen by George Keith, fifth Earl Marischal of Scotland in 1593.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] These institutions were merged by the Universities (Scotland) Act 1858 to form the University of Aberdeen.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The university is the fifth oldest in the English-speaking world and offers degrees in a full range of disciplines.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Its main campus is in Old Aberdeen in the north of the city and it currently has approximately 14,000 students.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The university's debating society is the oldest in Scotland, founded in 1848 as the King's College Debating Society.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Today, Aberdeen is consistently ranked among the top 200 universities in the world and is ranked within the top 20 universities in the United Kingdom.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was also named the 2019 Scottish University of the Year by The Times and Sunday Times Good University Guide.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] In early 2022, Aberdeen opened the Science Teaching Hub.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Robert Gordon's College (originally Robert Gordon's Hospital) was founded in 1750 by the merchant Robert Gordon, grandson of the map maker Robert Gordon of Straloch, and was further endowed in 1816 by Alexander Simpson of Collyhill.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Originally devoted to the instruction and maintenance of the sons of poor burgesses of guild and trade in the city, it was reorganised in 1881 as a day and night school for secondary and technical education.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] In 1903, the vocational education component of the college was designated a Central Institution and was renamed as the Robert Gordon Institute of Technology in 1965.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] In 1992, university status was awarded and it became Robert Gordon University.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The university has expanded and developed significantly in recent years, and was named Best Modern University in the UK for 2012 by *The Sunday Times*.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] It was previously *The Sunday Times* Scottish University of the Year for 2011, primarily because of its record on graduate employment.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is also home to two artistic schools: Gray's School of Art, founded in 1886, which is one of the oldest established colleges of art in the UK.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Scott Sutherland School of Architecture and Built Environment, was one of the first architectural schools to have its training courses recognised by the Royal Institute of British Architects.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Both are now part of Robert Gordon University and are based at its Garthdee campus.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] North East Scotland College has several campuses in the city and offers a wide variety of part-time and full-time courses leading to several different qualifications in science.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Agricultural College is based just outside Aberdeen, on the Craibstone Estate.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] This is situated beside the roundabout for Aberdeen Airport on the A96.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The college provides three services—Learning, Research and Consultancy.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The college features many land-based courses such as Agriculture, Countryside Management, Sustainable Environmental Management and Rural Business Management.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] There are a variety of courses from diplomas to master's degrees.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The Marine Laboratory Aberdeen, which specialises in fisheries, Macaulay Land Use Research Institute (soil science), and the Rowett Research Institute (animal nutrition) are some other higher education institutions.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen College of Performing Arts also provides full-time Drama and Musical Theatre training at Further Education level.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] There are currently 15 secondary schools and 54 primary schools which are run by the city council.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] There are a number of private schools in Aberdeen: Robert Gordon's College, Albyn School, St Margaret's School for Girls, the International School of Aberdeen and a Waldorf/Steiner School.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] State secondary schools in Aberdeen include Aberdeen Grammar School, Bridge of Don Academy, Bucksburn Academy, Cults Academy, Dyce Academy, Harlaw Academy, Hazlehead Academy, Lochside Academy, Northfield Academy, Oldmachar Academy and St Machar Academy.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p01] Independent primary and secondary schools in Aberdeen include Albyn School, Robert Gordon's College, St Margaret's School for Girls, and the International School of Aberdeen.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The city has a wide range of cultural activities, amenities, and museums, and is regularly visited by Scotland's National Arts Companies.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] It was awarded the Nicholson Trophy for the best-kept town at the Britain in Bloom contest in 1975.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery houses a collection of Impressionist, Victorian, Scottish and 20th-century British paintings as well as collections of silver and glass.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] It also includes The Alexander Macdonald Bequest, a collection of late 19th-century works donated by the museum's first benefactor and a constantly changing collection of contemporary work and regular visiting exhibitions.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery reopened in 2019 after a four-year refurbishment costing £34.6m.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Maritime Museum, located in Shiprow, tells the story of Aberdeen's links with the sea from the days of sail and clipper ships to the latest oil and gas exploration technology.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] It includes an 8.5-metre-high (28 ft) model of the Murchison oil production platform and a 19th-century assembly taken from Rattray Head lighthouse Provost Ross' House is the second oldest dwelling house in the city.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] It was built in 1593 and became the residence of Provost John Ross of Arnage in 1702.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The house retains some original medieval features, including a kitchen, fireplaces and beam-and-board ceilings.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The Gordon Highlanders Museum tells the story of one of Scotland's best known regiments.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Provost Skene's House on Flourmill Lane dates from 1545 and is the oldest surviving townhouse in the city.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] It reopened in October 2021 after significant refurbishment costing £3.8m.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] One of the new exhibitions is a Hall of Heroes featuring 100 Aberdonians who have made a significant contribution to the city.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The Tollbooth Museum on the Castlegate (currently closed to visitors) is a former jail, which first opened as a public museum in 1995.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Treasure Hub is a storage facility for Aberdeen Museums and Galleries containing over 100,000 items.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The store is open for infrequent tours, for example as part of Doors Open Day.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Marischal Museum holds the principal collections of the University of Aberdeen, comprising some 80,000 items in the areas of fine art, Scottish history and archaeology, and European, Mediterranean and Near Eastern archaeology.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The permanent displays and reference collections are augmented by regular temporary exhibitions, and since its closure to the public it now has a virtual online presence It closed to the public in 2008.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The King's Museum acts as the main museum of the university now.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Student Show, performed annually without interruption since 1921, under the auspices of the Aberdeen Students' Charities Campaign, is the longest-running of its kind in the United Kingdom.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] It is written, produced and performed by students and graduates of Aberdeen's universities and higher education institutions.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Since 1929—other than on a handful of occasions—it has been staged at His Majesty's Theatre.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] National festivals which visited Aberdeen in 2012 included the British Science Festival in September, hosted by the University of Aberdeen but with events also taking place at Robert Gordon University and at other venues across the city.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] In February 2012 the University of Aberdeen also hosted the Inter Varsity Folk Dance Festival, the longest-running folk festival in the United Kingdom.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Spectra, an annual light festival hosted in different locations across the city.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Nuart, a festival showcasing street art around the city.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] In 2020, the WayWORD Festival was launched by the University of Aberdeen WORD centre for creative writing.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] This yearly programme celebrates the arts through readings, performances, workshops and discussion panels.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] There have been many notable headliners including Val McDermid, Irvine Welsh and Douglas Stuart (writer).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Galas are held annually throughout the city, the most notable being the Culter Gala, which is usually held on the last Saturday of May.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The local dialect of Lowland Scots is often known as Doric and is spoken not just in the city, but across the northeast of Scotland.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] It differs somewhat from other Scots dialects: most noticeable are the pronunciation "f" for what is normally written "wh" and "ee" for what in standard English would usually be written "oo" (Scots "ui").
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Every year the annual Doric Festival takes place in Aberdeenshire to celebrate the history of the north-east's language.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Scotland's oldest newspaper the *Press and Journal*, a local and regional newspaper first published in 1747.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The *Press and Journal* and its sister paper the tabloid *Evening Express* are printed six days a week by Aberdeen Journals.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] There was one free newspaper, the *Aberdeen Citizen*.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] BBC Scotland has a network studio production base in the city's Beechgrove area, and BBC Aberdeen produces *The Beechgrove Potting Shed* for radio while Tern Television produces *The Beechgrove Garden*.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The city is also home to STV North (formerly Grampian Television), which produces the regional news programmes such as *STV News at Six*, as well as local commercials.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The station, based at Craigshaw Business Park in Tullos, was based at larger studios in Queens Cross from September 1961 until June 2003.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Music venues include the Music Hall and the P&J Live.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen region has given its name to a number of dishes, including the Aberdeen buttery (also known as "rowie") and Aberdeen Sausage.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] In 2015, a study was published in The Scotsman which analysed the presence of branded fast food outlets in Scotland.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Of the ten towns and cities analysed, Aberdeen was found to have the lowest per capita concentration, with just 0.12 stores per 1,000 inhabitants.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The public health service in Scotland, NHS Scotland provides for the people of Aberdeen through the NHS Grampian health board.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Albyn Hospital is a private hospital located in the west end of the city.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen City Council is responsible for city-owned infrastructure which is paid for by a mixture of Council Tax and income from the Scottish Government.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure and services run by the council include: nursery, primary and secondary education, roads, clearing snow in winter, city wardens, maintaining parks, refuse collection, economic development, public analyst, public mortuary, street cleaning and street lighting.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure in private hands includes electricity, gas and telecoms.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Water and sewerage services are provided by Scottish Water.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The first ever recorded game of football, was outlined by teacher David Wedderburn in his book "Vocabula" written in 1633, during his time teaching at Aberdeen Grammar School.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] There is one Aberdeen-based football club in the SPFL.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] (The Dons) play in the Scottish Premiership at Pittodrie Stadium.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The club won the European Cup Winners Cup and the European Super Cup in 1983, the Scottish Premier League Championship four times (1955, 1980, 1984 and 1985), and the Scottish Cup eight times (1947, 1970, 1982, 1983, 1984, 1986, 1990 and 2025).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of Alex Ferguson, Aberdeen was a major force in British football during the 1980s.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of McInnes the team won the 2014 Scottish League Cup and followed it up with a second-place league finish for the first time in more than 20 years in the following season.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] But it was over the last few seasons that results stagnated and McInnes was replaced by former Aberdeen and Newcastle player Stephen Glass.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Cove Rangers, as of season 2024-25 play in League One, at the Balmoral Stadium in the suburb of Cove Bay.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Cove won the Highland Football League championship in 2001, 2008, 2009, 2013 and 2019, winning the League Two play-offs in 2019 and earning promotion.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] At the point at which the 2019/20 League Two season was curtailed due to the COVID-19 pandemic, Cove were sitting top of the League Two table and were promoted as Champions.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Other local teams include Banks o'Dee who play at Spain Park in the Highland Football League and members of the SJFA North Region; Culter, Dyce, Stoneywood Parkvale, Glentanar, Sunnybank Hall Russell United, Bridge of Don Thistle and Hermes.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen hosted Caledonia Reds, a Scottish rugby team, before they merged with the Glasgow Warriors in 1998.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] In 2005 the President of the SRU said it was hoped eventually to establish a professional team in Aberdeen.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] In November 2008 the city hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Canada, with Scotland winning 41–0.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] In November 2010 the city once again hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Samoa, with Scotland winning 19–16.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Warriors rugby league team play in the Rugby League Conference Division One.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The Warriors also run Under 15's and 17's teams.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Grammar School won the Saltire Schools Cup in 2011.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The Royal Aberdeen Golf Club, founded in 1780 is the sixth oldest golf club in the world, and hosted the Senior British Open in 2005, and the amateur team event the Walker Cup in 2011.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Royal Aberdeen also hosted the Scottish Open in 2014, won by Justin Rose.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The club has a second course, and there are public golf courses at Auchmill, Balnagask, Hazlehead and King's Links.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] There are new courses planned for the area, including world-class facilities with major financial backing, the city and shire are set to become important in golf tourism.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] In Summer 2012, Donald Trump opened a new state of the art golf course at Menie, just north of the city, as the Trump International Golf Links, Scotland.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Ice hockey in Aberdeen boasts a history that began in the early 20th century.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Glaciarium on Forbesfield Road became a hub for games, featuring teams like the Grammar School Former Pupils and the Aberdeen Ice Hockey Club.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] However, the sport all but died out with the onset of WW1.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The sport was revived in the city with the opening of the Linx Ice Arena in 1992.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Lynx plays in the Scottish National League and is based at the Linx Ice Arena.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Founded in 2005, they won back to back regular season titles in 2022-23 and 2023–24 and won the play-off championship in 2015-16 and again in 2024–25.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] They regularly sell out home games and are the second best supported sports team in the city after Aberdeen FC.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The City of Aberdeen Swim Team (COAST) was based in Northfield swimming pool, but since the opening of the Aberdeen Aquatics Centre in 2014, it is now based there, as it has a 50 m pool as opposed to the 25 m pool at Northfield.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The team comprises several smaller swimming clubs and has enjoyed success throughout Scotland and in international competitions.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Three of the team's swimmers qualified for the 2006 Commonwealth Games.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] There are four boat clubs that row on the River Dee: Aberdeen Boat Club (ABC), Aberdeen Schools Rowing Association (ASRA), Aberdeen University Boat Club (AUBC) and Robert Gordon University Boat Club (RGUBC).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The city has one national league side, Stoneywood-Dyce.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Local "Grades" cricket has been played in Aberdeen since 1884.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeenshire were the 2009 and 2014 Scottish National Premier League and Scottish Cup Champions.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen University Shinty Club (Scottish Gaelic: Club Camanachd Oilthigh Obar Dheathain) is the oldest constituted shinty club in the world, dating back to 1861.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The city council operates public tennis courts in various parks including an indoor tennis centre at Westburn Park.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The Beach Leisure Centre is home to a climbing wall, gymnasium and a swimming pool.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] There are numerous swimming pools dotted around the city notably the largest, the Bon Accord Baths which closed down in 2008.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] In common with many other major towns and cities in the UK, Aberdeen has an active roller derby league, Granite City Roller Derby.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Roughnecks American football club is a new team that started in 2012 and is the first team that Aberdeen has witnessed since the Granite City Oilers that began in 1986 and were wound up in the mid-1990s.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Oilers Floorball Club was founded in 2007.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The club initially attracted a range of experienced Scandinavian and other European players who were studying in Aberdeen.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Since their formation, Aberdeen Oilers have played in the British Floorball Northern League and went on to win the league in the 2008/09 season.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The club played a major role in setting up a ladies league in Scotland.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The Oilers' ladies team ended up second in the first ladies league season (2008/09).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] One of the earliest known disasters is the Storegga Slide in the mesolithic period in 6225–6170 BCE which caused tsunami waves to hit North sea coastal areas, with wave heights of 3-6 meters in the north east Scotland areas.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] In 1876, the River Dee ferryboat disaster took place when 32 people drowned in the mouth of the River Dee.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The 20th century includes a World War II disaster when in 1943, a Luftwaffe raid dropped 129 bombs on Aberdeen resulting in 125 deaths..
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] In 1964, a typhoid outbreak occurred with 400 cases and three fatalities.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] In 1983, the Aberdeen taxi driver George Murdoch was killed, the murder case is unsolved.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] In modern time, accidents have been related with offshore drilling.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] In 1988, the oil platform Piper Alpha, located 190 km north-east of Aberdeen, exploded and collapsed, killing 165.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The accident is the worst ever offshore oil and gas disaster in terms of lives lost.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Hazlehead Park contains a memorial to the crew. .
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] In 1995, the Bristow Helicopters Flight 56C was struck by lightning and emergency landed in the sea.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] The 18 crew and passengers on board survived.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] In 2009, the Bond Offshore Helicopters Flight 85N crashed 20 km north-east of Peterhead, while returning from an oil platform to Aberdeen Airport.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aberdeen-p02] Johnston Gardens contains a memorial to the deceased.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The town survived the dissolution of the abbey in 1538, and by the 18th and 19th centuries, with the building of Abingdon Lock in 1790 and the Wilts & Berks Canal in 1810, Abingdon was on important routes for goods transport.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] In 1856 the Abingdon Railway opened, linking the town with the Great Western Railway.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The canal was abandoned in 1906 but a voluntary trust is now working to restore and re-open it.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Abingdon railway station was closed to passengers in September 1963.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The line remained open for goods until 1984, its role including serving the MG car factory, which operated from 1929 to 1980.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Abingdon's brewery, Morland, makers of Old Speckled Hen ale, was taken over and closed in 1999; the site of the brewery has been redeveloped into housing.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The rock band Radiohead formed in 1985 when its members were studying at Abingdon School, a day and boarding independent secondary school.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The 2011 Census recorded the parish's population as 33,130.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] A Neolithic stone hand axe was found at Abingdon.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Petrological analysis in 1940 identified the stone as epidotised tuff from Stake Pass in the Lake District, 250 mi (400 km) to the north.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Stone axes from the same source have been found at Sutton Courtenay, Alvescot, Kencot and Minster Lovell.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Abingdon has been occupied from the early to middle Iron Age and the remains of a late Iron Age defensive enclosure (or oppidum) lies below the town centre.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The oppidum was in use throughout the Roman occupation.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] A Neolithic causewayed enclosure was found in Abingdon, dating to the 36th or 37th century BC.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] It was found in 1926 while quarrying for gravel, and was partly excavated in 1926 and 1927 by E.T.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Subsequent excavations took place in 1954 and 1963.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] A Roman villa and subsequent Saxon farmstead buildings have been excavated at Barton Court Farm.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Abingdon Abbey was founded in Saxon times, possibly around 676, but its early history is confused by numerous legends, invented to raise its status and explain the place name.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The name seems to mean 'Hill of a man named Æbba, or a woman named Æbbe', possibly the saint to whom St Ebbe's Church in Oxford was dedicated (Æbbe of Coldingham or a different Æbbe of Oxford).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] However, Abingdon stands in a valley and not on a hill.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] It is thought that the name was first given to a place on Boars Hill above Chilswell, and the name was transferred to its present site when the Abbey was moved.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] In 1084, William the Conqueror celebrated Easter at the Abbey and it is possible that his son Henry I received some schooling at the abbey.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] In the 13th and 14th centuries, Abingdon was a flourishing agricultural centre with an extensive trade in wool and a famous weaving and clothing manufacturing industry.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The abbot seems to have held a market from very early times and charters for the holding of markets and fairs were granted by various sovereigns, from Edward I to George II.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] In 1337 there was a famous riot in protest at the Abbot's control of this market in which several of the monks were killed.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] After the abbey's dissolution in 1538, the town sank into decay.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] In 1556, upon receiving a representation of its pitiable condition, Mary I granted a charter incorporating the town as a borough, governed by a mayor, two bailiffs, twelve chief burgesses and sixteen secondary burgesses, the mayor to be clerk of the market, coroner and a JP.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The present Christ's Hospital originally belonged to the Guild of the Holy Cross, on the dissolution of which Edward VI founded the almshouses instead, under its present name.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The borough elected one member of parliament; this right would continue until the Redistribution of Seats Act 1885.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The 1556 charter also catered for the appointment of a town clerk and other officers, and the borough boundaries were described in detail.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Later charters, from Elizabeth I, James I, James II, George II and George III, made no considerable change.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] James II changed the style of the corporation to that of a mayor, twelve aldermen and twelve burgesses.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Abingdon became the county town of Berkshire sometime after receiving its charter in 1556.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Assize courts were held in Abingdon from 1570, but in the 17th century it was vying with Reading for county town status.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The county hall and court house were built between 1678 and 1682, to assert this status.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The building, now the Abingdon County Hall Museum, was reputedly designed by Christopher Kempster, who worked with Sir Christopher Wren.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Abingdon borough police was the police force responsible for policing the Borough until 1889.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] It was formed as a result of the Municipal Corporations Act 1835.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The force was amalgamated into the Berkshire Constabulary following the Local Government Act 1888, which required all boroughs with populations of less than 10,000 to amalgamate their police forces with their adjoining county constabulary.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Today, the area is policed by the successor to Berkshire Constabulary, Thames Valley Police.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] In 1790 Abingdon Lock was built, replacing navigation via the Swift Ditch.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] In 1810, the Wilts & Berks Canal opened, linking Abingdon with Semington on the Kennet and Avon Canal.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Abingdon became a key link between major industrial centres such as Bristol, London, Birmingham and the Black Country.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] In 1856 the Abingdon Railway opened, linking the town with the Great Western Railway at Radley.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] However, Abingdon's failure to engage fully with the railway revolution, accepting only a branch line, sidelined the town in favour of Reading which became the County Town in 1869.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The Wilts & Berks Canal was abandoned in 1906 but a voluntary trust is now working to restore and re-open it.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The line remained open for goods until 1984, including serving the MG car factory, which opened in 1929 and closed in October 1980 as part of a British Leyland rationalisation plan.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The nearest railway station is Radley, two miles (3.2 km) away.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Much of the original Abingdon branch line is now a cyclepath, whilst the land on which the station stood has been extensively redeveloped, and is now the site of a large Waitrose store and surrounded by a large number of new flats and houses.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The corporation was reformed, under the Municipal Corporations Act 1835, but was abolished under the Local Government Act 1972, which enacted extensive local government reorganisation across England and Wales with effect from 1 April 1974.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] As a result of this reorganisation, Berkshire County Council's northern boundary was much reduced and Abingdon's governance was transferred to Oxfordshire, with the town becoming the seat of the new Vale of White Horse District Council, and Abingdon becoming a civil parish with a town council.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Since the 1980s, Abingdon has played host to a number of information communication companies, with many based in the town's respective business and science parks.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] As a consequence, and owing to Abingdon's proximity to academic and scientific institutions in Oxford, the town has seen an influx of young professionals taking residence in the town's many residential areas such as Peachcroft.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The town was sometimes historically called "Abingdon-on-Thames", but the official name of the borough (as given in statutes from the Municipal Corporations Act 1835 to the Local Government Act 1972 and all intervening Ordnance Survey maps) was simply "Abingdon".
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Local councillors voted in November 2011 to change the official name of the town to "Abingdon-on-Thames", and the change took effect on 23 February 2012.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Sport and recreation facilities include the White Horse Leisure and Tennis Centre, Tilsley Park and the Southern Town Park.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Abingdon had four cinemas but all have closed.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The last was the Regal, which closed in 1989.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] It stood derelict for 24 years until it was demolished in 2003 and replaced by housing development, Regal Close.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The Unicorn theatre was built in an area called The Checkers Hall in the ruins of the Abbey buildings and shows plays and films on an irregular basis.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] In addition, a new cinema, called the Abbey Cinema has been built in one of the town council buildings and operates in conjunction with the Regal in Evesham.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The local newspapers are *The Oxford Times*, *Oxford Mail* and *Abingdon Herald*.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The *Oxfordshire Guardian*, a free newspaper, was based in Abingdon for many years and was founded as the *South Oxfordshire Courier* until its closure in 2018.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Local radio and television stations are shared with Oxford, although ITV retains a news gathering centre in nearby Milton Park (formerly having a broadcasting studio in the town) for ITV Meridian.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Historically the ITV franchise was ITV Central.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Local analogue radio is provided by BBC Radio Oxford, Greatest Hits Radio and Heart South (historically 'Fox FM' and later 'Heart Thames Valley'), while the town is also covered by the Oxfordshire DAB multiplex.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] There was a Six TV local TV channel until 2009 and the town's further education college was the home to That's TV studios for Oxfordshire until it relocated to Oxford Science Park.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The Tesco Extra store west of the town is the largest supermarket in Abingdon and has historically been one of the most profitable Tesco stores in the country.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Nearby is the Fairacres Retail Park, thought to be the first retail park in the UK and recently redeveloped, which includes Argos, Subway, B & M, Dreams and Pets at Home stores.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] It originally had two long established Abingdon retailers—Vineys Home Furnishings (now part of the Lee Longlands chain but retains its name) and Mays Carpets (now part of the Carpetright chain and has re-branded accordingly).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] In the town centre, many independent stores, estate agents and charity shops make up the Bury Street shopping centre as major high street names have chosen to go to other towns.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The town centre of Abingdon was renovated in 2012 as part of the council's redevelopment plan, with the 1970s shopping precinct converted to look more modern.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The roads around the area have been changed: notably the one-way system around the centre has been partially changed to two-way.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] While this has slightly reduced traffic within the historic town centre, congestion has greatly increased elsewhere.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Local businesses have also complained that the increased traffic has driven shoppers away.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Redevelopment of the Old Gaol site, most recently a leisure centre, began in 2010.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The first stage was demolishing the 1970s additions and swimming pool extension.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The Gaol has been converted into luxury flats, shops and restaurants, with access to the riverside.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Abingdon has two non-League football teams: Abingdon United F.C., who compete in the Combined Counties League Premier Division North and play at The Armadillo Energy Stadium, and Abingdon Town F.C., who play at Culham Road.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Abingdon Golf Club/North Berks Golf Club (now defunct) was first mentioned in 1876.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The club disappeared at the time of the Second World War The Oxford Saints American football Club play their games in Abingdon at Tilsley Park and are one of the longest-running American football clubs in the UK, founded in 1983.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Abingdon is home to Abingdon Rowing Club, with members from 13 to 80 years old.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] It has had many successes at local and national races, and also holds its own Abingdon Head race in April, one of the main events in the Abingdon Calendar.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Abingdon Amblers changed its name to Abingdon Athletics Club.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] They train at Tilsley Park and take part in county cross-country leagues.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Abingdon RUFC was formed at the Queens Hotel on 27 February 1931.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] During the 1930s the club was based at the Queens Hotel and games were played on the council owned recreation ground at Caldecott Road.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Immediately after the Second World War the club moved to outside the RAF camp (now Dalton Barracks) which offered on-site changing facilities and later a pitch inside the camp.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] At the start of the Suez Crisis in 1956 play temporarily returned to the Caldecott Road site because of security risks.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] This period saw the formation of the ill-fated Abingdon Sports Club; an amalgamation of the town's rugby, cricket and hockey clubs and the bid to establish a sporting centre at Hales Meadow.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] In a short time the ground was developed and a pavilion erected but the organisation was plagued with financial difficulties and very soon dissolved with hockey disbanding and Abingdon Rugby remaining at the site as tenants to the cricket club.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] In the mid-1980s a determined effort was made to acquire grounds and a clubhouse dedicated to rugby.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] In 2022 Abingdon Womens Rugby Club known as “The Albatrosses” was formed and they currently play in the Inner Warrior League.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The current base at the town's Southern Sports Park was opened by former Abingdon MP John Patten in 1989.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Abingdon has had members representing the county, progressing to first-class level and on to international status in the Six Nations Tournament.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The Abingdon Sevens traditionally opens the Home Counties' playing season and has attracted sides from throughout the country and beyond.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Initiated in 1956 as a one-off tournament to celebrate the town's 400th anniversary of receiving a Royal Charter, it proved so successful that the competition has been held on an annual basis ever since.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Several years ago it was decided to introduce the youngsters of Abingdon to Club Rugby.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The Youth Section has 200 playing members from the ages of 6 to 18.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] In 2013–14 Abingdon RFC's president, Paul Murphy MBE, was also the president of the RFU.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Since 2016, Oxford Rugby League have played in Abingdon at Abingdon School's Tilsley Park.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Malting and brewing had been carried out for centuries in Abingdon, and by Victorian times there were many malthouses in the town.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Eventually, the Morland Brewery predominated.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] It had been established by a farmer, John Morland in 1711.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Morland's most famous ale was Old Speckled Hen, named after an early prototype MG car.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Greene King Brewery bought Morland for £182 million in 1999, closed the brewery and moved production to Bury St Edmunds in Suffolk.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The site of the brewery has been redeveloped into housing.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The Maltings was demolished and is now a mixed residential area and council offices.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] In 2010, a craft brewery, Loose Cannon, reinstated brewing in the town at the Drayton Road Industrial Estate and sells its beers locally, including on draught at some local pubs.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The Pavlova and Gloria leather works were major employers but both are now closed.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Alfred Booth and Company of Liverpool traded with the Pavlova Leather Syndicate from 1860, bought a share in it in 1917–18 and took it over in 1921.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] In May 1947 at the annual British Industries Fair in Birmingham, Pavlova advertised doe skins, chamois, lambskins and goatskins, much of it as suede, for uses including shoes, gloves and belts.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] In 1958 Pavlova's site covered 35 acres (14 ha), employed neary 200 people and included a staff sports field.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] At that time its factory still processed imported skins of sheep, lamb and goat, mainly to make suede.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Garner Group took over the Booth Group in 1979 and became Garner Booth.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Pittards plc took over Garner Booth in 1987 and became Pittard Garner.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Hemp-dressing, matting, sackcloth and carpet–weaving were a substantial source of employment in the early 19th century and the first satisfactory yarn and cloth made from jute were produced in Abingdon.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] There were 22 sacking manufacturers and 3 matting manufacturers in the town in 1830.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] A carpet factory was built on the island between the Mill race and the river – opposite The Nag's Head.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The Abingdon Carpet Manufacturing Company was run by George Shepherd from 1879 and produced carpets, rugs, and rush and coconut-fibre matting.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Foreign competition led to its closure in the early 1930s.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] A clothing factory was built on the West side of the lower end of St.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The site was owned by a hemp and linen manufacturer called James Varley who had lost much of his business in a fire in 1838 and became the property of John Hyde and Son clothes dealers and frock makers, in about 1844.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] This business prospered, especially during the American Civil War and lasted until 1931.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Industrially, Abingdon was best known for the MG car factory, which opened in 1929.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] 1,155,032 cars were made at the plant over the following 51 years until British Leyland closed it on 24 October 1980.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Subsequent cars sold under the MG brand have since been produced either at Longbridge in Birmingham or at SAIC's factories in China.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The company was founded in 1924 and moved its business alongside the Pavlova Leather Factory in 1929.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] By the outbreak of the Second World War, MG was established as one of the most popular brands of sports car in Britain.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] During the war the factory was used for a variety of war work.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] After the war, the MG factory continued to turn out increasing volumes of popular sports cars that were available at competitive prices, but it closed in October 1980 on the demise of the ageing but still popular MG MGB range, and was demolished within months.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The headquarters of the MG Car Club, founded in 1930, is at 11 & 12 Cemetery Road, next to the old factory offices.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] A police station was built in its place, which was later extended with the addition of more cells, as Oxford's police station could not be extended further.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The Abingdon Science Park includes the global headquarters of Sophos, an anti-virus company and Penlon Ltd, a medical equipment company, (their previous site, near the former railway station, has been redeveloped as residential housing).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Another major employer is the British head office of the German appliance company Miele.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] RM, an educational computing supplier, commonly refer to themselves as being Abingdon-based, which is technically true—even though their HQ is actually in nearby Milton Park, Milton, they have an Abingdon post code (as does the rest of Milton Park).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Abingdon also has a business park which has offices for several local, national and international companies including, until recently, Vodafone (acquired as part of its takeover of Mannesmann in 2000) and Northern Rock bank.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Many inhabitants work in Oxford or commute by rail to London, from nearby Didcot.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The Army now occupies Dalton Barracks, which, prior to 1993, was the Royal Air Force station RAF Abingdon.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Abingdon is 9 miles (14 km) south of Oxford, 15 mi (24 km) south-east of Witney and 22 mi (35 km) north of Newbury in the flat valley of the Thames on its west (right) bank, where the small river Ock flows in from the Vale of White Horse.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] It is on the A415 between Witney and Dorchester, adjacent to the A34 trunk road, linking it with the M4 and M40 motorways.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The B4017 and A4183 also link the town, both being part of the old A34 and often heavily congested.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Local bus services to Oxford and the surrounding areas are run by the Oxford Bus Company, its sister company Thames Travel and smaller independent companies.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] However, in recent years, urban expansion has brought Radley railway station close to the town's northeastern limits.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The small, primarily stopping-service, railway stations at Culham and Radley are both just over two miles (3.2 km) from the town centre.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Abingdon's eastern ring-road and newest suburbs are connected by footpath and cycleway from Radley.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Culham station was called "Abingdon Road" when it first opened in 1844, being the nearest station to the town at that time.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] It was renamed "Culham" when the Abingdon Railway branch line to Abingdon railway station was opened in 1856.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] That branch line initially connected to the main line at Abingdon Junction, before being extended to Radley station when that opened in 1873.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The branch line from Radley to Abingdon closed to passengers in 1963.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The nearest major stations with taxi ranks are Oxford (6 miles/9.7 km) and Didcot Parkway (8 miles/13 km).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] All are managed by Great Western Railway.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Frequent express buses operate between the local railway stations and Abingdon, run by Oxford Bus Company and its sister company Thames Travel.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] There are three tiers of local government covering Abingdon, at parish (town), district and county level: Abingdon-on-Thames Town Council, Vale of White Horse District Council, and Oxfordshire County Council.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The town council meets at the Guildhall on Bridge Street and has its offices in the adjoining Roysse Court.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Parts of the Guildhall date back to the 15th century, having been originally part of the Abbey complex.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Control of the town council has passed between the Liberal Democrats and Conservatives in recent years.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The incumbent member of parliament for Oxford West and Abingdon is Layla Moran (Liberal Democrat).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Abingdon was first incorporated as a borough in 1556.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The borough covered parts of the parishes of St Helen and St Nicolas; both parishes also included rural areas beyond the borough boundary.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The borough was reformed to become a municipal borough in 1836 under the Municipal Corporations Act 1835, which standardised how most boroughs operated across the country.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The municipal borough was abolished in 1974 under the Local Government Act 1972, which also transferred the town from Berkshire to Oxfordshire.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] District-level functions passed to the Vale of White Horse District Council.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] A successor parish covering the area of the former borough was created called Abingdon, with its council taking the name Abingdon Town Council.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The parish was formally renamed to Abingdon-on-Thames in 2012.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Of the Benedictine Abingdon Abbey there remains a Perpendicular gateway and ruins of the mainly Early English prior's house, the guest house and other fragments.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Other remains from the former abbey include the Unicorn Theatre and the Long Gallery, which are still used for plays and functions including an annual craft fair.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Nicolas' Church, parts of which were built in 1180, is near the museum.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Abingdon Bridge over the Thames, near St Helen's Church, was built in 1416 and was widened or altered in 1790, 1828, 1927 and 1929.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Abbey Gateway between the Abingdon County Hall Museum and the Guildhall remains a point of local importance.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Abingdon has the remains of a motte-and-bailey castle, which can be found to the north of the town centre surrounded by trees within a housing estate.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Originally built of wood or stone, it was a fortification on a raised earthwork called a motte surrounded by a protective ditch.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] There is a Second World War FW3/28A pillbox by the River Ock near Marcham Road.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] A prison, built by prisoners of the Napoleonic Wars in 1811, is on the south edge of town next to the Thames.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] In the 1970s the prison was converted into a leisure centre.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] In 2011 the site was developed into residential and commercial premises.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] According to local legend, prior to its conversion in the 1970s, the prison was haunted by the ghost of an eight-year-old boy who, after being convicted for arson in the mid-19th century, became the youngest person in the UK to be executed by hanging.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The Roysse Room was the site of Abingdon School (then 'Roysse's School') from 1563 until it moved to its current site after an indenture by John Roysse, who had been born and educated in Abingdon before he moved to London.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The room is now part of the civic offices.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Helen's Church dates from around 1100 and is the second-widest church in England, having five aisles and being 10 feet (3 m) wider than it is long.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The tower of St Helen's Church has a modern ring of ten bells, cast by the Whitechapel Bell Foundry in 2005 and hung in a new frame with new fittings by White's of Appleton in 2006.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Abingdon's county hall by the main market square, built in 1677–1680 reputedly by Christopher Kempster, stands on columns, leaving the ground floor open for a market and other functions.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] It was once hailed by Nikolaus Pevsner with the comment "Of the free-standing town halls of England with open ground floors this is the grandest".
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] It now houses the Abingdon County Hall Museum and is run by Historic England.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Bun-throwing is an Abingdon tradition that began with the 1761 Coronation of King George III.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] This longstanding tradition of the town has local dignitaries throwing buns (5,000 buns in 2018) from the roof of the Abingdon County Hall Museum into crowds assembled in the market square below on specific days of celebration (such as royal marriages, coronations and jubilees).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The museum has a collection of the buns, dried and varnished, dating back to bun-throwings of the 19th century.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] To date there have been 35 bun-throwing events.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Every October, the Abingdon Michaelmas Fair is held.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Extending to the length of a mile, the fair is thought to be the longest and oldest street fair in Europe.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] It runs through the Market Place, High Street, and Ock Street.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The fair was originally a hiring fair, designed to allow farmworkers from rural areas to find work in the town following the Black Death in 1348/9.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The fair, previously run on the first Monday and Tuesday before 11 October each year, had its dates extended in 2024 to also run one day earlier, from the Sunday to the Tuesday.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The much smaller Runaway Fair is run the Monday following the Michaelmas Fair, and was traditionally for workers who were unsatisfied with their employment after the first week, and sought to "run away" and return to the town to find better job opportunities.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Abingdon has a very old and still active Morris dancing tradition, passed on since before the folk dance and song revivals in the 19th century.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Every year a mayor of Ock Street is elected by the inhabitants of Ock Street; he then parades through the town preceded by the famous Horns of Ock Street, a symbol of Abingdon's Morris Dance troupe.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The Friends of Abingdon's Unicorn Theatre, housed in the old Abbey buildings, is the site of first productions of many stage adaptations of Terry Pratchett's *Discworld* novels by Stephen Briggs.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] Old Speckled Hen ale was originally brewed by Morland's of Abingdon to commemorate the MG factory in the town.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] It continues to be brewed by Greene King along with several complementary beers.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The rock band Radiohead formed at Abingdon School in 1985.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/abingdon-on-thames] The following people and military units have received the Freedom of the Town of **Abingdon-on-Thames**.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Named in honour of Adelaide of Saxe-Meiningen, wife of King William IV, the city was founded in 1836 as the planned capital for a freely settled British colony in Australia.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Colonel William Light, one of Adelaide's founding fathers, designed the city centre and chose its location close to the River Torrens.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Light's design, now listed as national heritage, set out the city centre in a grid layout known as "Light's Vision", interspaced by wide boulevards and large public squares, and entirely surrounded by park lands.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Colonial Adelaide was noted for its leading examples of religious freedom and progressive political reforms and became known as the "City of Churches" due to its diversity of faiths.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] It was Australia's third-most populous city until the postwar era.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Today, Adelaide is one of Australia's most visited travel destinations and hosts many festivals and sporting events, such as the Adelaide 500, Tour Down Under, Gather Round, LIV Golf Adelaide, and the Adelaide Fringe, the world's second largest annual arts festival.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Adelaide also hosts men's tennis with an ATP 250 event and women's tennis with a WTA 500 event, and will also become the new host of the Australian MotoGP Grand Prix from 2027.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The city has also been renowned for its automotive industry, having been the original host of the Australian Grand Prix in the FIA Formula One World Championship from 1985 to 1995.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Other features include its food and wine industries, its coastline and hills, its large defence and manufacturing operations, and its emerging space sector, including the Australian Space Agency being headquartered there.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] With one of the world's largest foreign-born populations, Adelaide has consistently ranked within the top-ten most liveable cities globally for much of the 21st century, being named in 2021 the most liveable city in the country and third in the world.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Its aesthetic appeal has also been recognised by *Architectural Digest*, which ranked Adelaide as the most beautiful city in the world in 2024.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] As South Australia's government and commercial centre, Adelaide is the site of many governmental and financial institutions.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Most of these are concentrated in the central business district along the cultural boulevards of North Terrace and King William Street.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Adelaide has also been classed as a Gamma + level global city as categorised by the Globalization and World Cities Research Network, with the city further linking economic regions to the worldwide economy.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is connected by extensive bus, train and tram networks, all of which are operated by Adelaide Metro, with its main railway terminus at the Adelaide railway station.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The city is also served by Adelaide Airport and Port Adelaide, both of which are among the busiest airports and seaports in Australia, respectively.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The amount of time Aboriginal people have been living in the area around modern-day Adelaide has been described as "millennia", "tens of thousands of years", "thousands of generations", or "innumerable generations".
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] At Hallett Cove Conservation Park in Adelaide's southern suburbs, archaeological evidence of Aboriginal culture has been found dating back 40,000 years.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The area was originally inhabited by the Kaurna people, one of many Aboriginal tribes in South Australia.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The city and parklands area also known as *Tarndanyangga* *Tandanya*, *Tarndanya* or *Tarntanya*.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The name means 'male red kangaroo rock', referring to a rock formation on the site that has now been destroyed.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The surrounding area was an open, grassy plain with patches of trees and shrubs, which had been managed by hundreds of generations.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Kaurna country encompassed the plains stretching north and south of Tarntanya, as well as the wooded foothills of the Mt Lofty Ranges.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The River Torrens was known as the Karrawirra Pari (Red Gum forest river).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] About 300 Kaurna populated the Adelaide area, and were referred to by the settlers as the Cowandilla.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The more than 20 local clans across the plain lived seminomadic lives, with extensive mound settlements where huts were built repeatedly over centuries and a complex social structure, including a class of sorcerers separated from regular society.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Within a few decades of European settlement of South Australia, Kaurna culture was almost completely lost, with the last speaker of Kaurna language having died in 1929.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Extensive documentation by early missionaries and other researchers has enabled a modern revival of both, which has included a commitment by local and state governments to rename or include Kaurna names for many local places.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Based on the ideas of Edward Gibbon Wakefield about colonial reform, Robert Gouger petitioned the British government to create a new colony in Australia, resulting in the passage of the South Australia Act 1834.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Physical establishment of the colony began with the arrival of the first British colonisers in February 1836, followed by the commencement of colonial government in South Australia on 28 December 1836.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Proclaimed by the governor near The Old Gum Tree in what is now the suburb of Glenelg North, this day is annually commemorated in South Australia as Proclamation Day.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Named for Queen Adelaide, the site of the colony's capital was surveyed and laid out by Colonel William Light, the first surveyor-general of South Australia, with his own original, unique and topographically sensitive design.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Adelaide was established as a planned colony of free settlers, promising civil liberties and freedom from religious persecution, based upon the ideas of Edward Gibbon Wakefield.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Wakefield had read accounts of Australian settlement while in prison in London for attempting to abduct an heiress, and realised that the eastern colonies suffered from a lack of available labour, due to the practice of giving land grants to all arrivals.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Wakefield's idea was for the Government to survey and sell the land at a rate that would maintain land values high enough to be unaffordable for labourers and journeymen.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Funds raised from the sale of land were to be used to bring out working-class emigrants, who would have to work hard for the monied settlers to ever afford their own land.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] As a result of this policy, Adelaide does not share the convict settlement history of other Australian cities like Sydney, Brisbane and Hobart.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] As it was believed that in a colony of free settlers there would be little crime, no provision was made for a gaol in Colonel Light's 1837 plan.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] But by mid-1837 the *South Australian Register* was warning of escaped convicts from New South Wales and tenders for a temporary gaol were sought.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Following a burglary, a murder, and two attempted murders in Adelaide during March 1838, Governor Hindmarsh created the South Australian Police Force (now the South Australia Police) in April 1838 under 21-year-old Henry Inman.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The first sheriff, Samuel Smart, was wounded during a robbery, and on 2 May 1838 one of the offenders, Michael Magee, became the first person to be hanged in South Australia.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] William Baker Ashton was appointed governor of the temporary gaol in 1839, and in 1840 George Strickland Kingston was commissioned to design Adelaide's new gaol.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Construction of Adelaide Gaol commenced in 1841.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's early history was marked by economic uncertainty and questionable leadership.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The first governor of South Australia, John Hindmarsh, clashed frequently with others, in particular the Resident Commissioner, James Hurtle Fisher.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The rural area surrounding Adelaide was surveyed by Light in preparation to sell a total of over 405 km2 (156 sq mi) of land.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's early economy started to get on its feet in 1838 with the arrival of livestock from Victoria, New South Wales and Tasmania.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Wool production provided an early basis for the South Australian economy.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] By 1860, wheat farms had been established from Encounter Bay in the south to Clare in the north.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] He was criticised for his response to the Maria massacre.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Gawler was recalled and replaced by George Edward Grey in 1841.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Grey slashed public expenditure against heavy opposition, although its impact was negligible at this point: silver was discovered in Glen Osmond that year, agriculture was well underway, and other mines sprung up all over the state, aiding Adelaide's commercial development.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The city exported meat, wool, wine, fruit and wheat by the time Grey left in 1845, contrasting with a low point in 1842 when one-third of Adelaide houses were abandoned.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Trade links with the rest of the Australian states were established after the Murray River was successfully navigated in 1853 by Francis Cadell, an Adelaide resident.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] South Australia became a self-governing colony in 1856 with the ratification of a new constitution by the British parliament.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Secret ballots were introduced, and a bicameral parliament was elected on 9 March 1857, by which time 109,917 people lived in the province.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] In 1860, the Thorndon Park reservoir was opened, providing an alternative water source to the now turbid River Torrens.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Gas street lighting was implemented in 1867, the University of Adelaide was founded in 1874, the South Australian Art Gallery opened in 1881 and the Happy Valley Reservoir opened in 1896.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] In the 1890s Australia was affected by a severe economic depression, ending a hectic era of land booms and tumultuous expansionism.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Financial institutions in Melbourne and banks in Sydney closed.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The national fertility rate fell and immigration was reduced to a trickle.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The value of South Australia's exports nearly halved.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Drought and poor harvests from 1884 compounded the problems, with some families leaving for Western Australia.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Adelaide was not as badly hit as the larger gold-rush cities of Sydney and Melbourne, and silver and lead discoveries at Broken Hill provided some relief.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Only one year of deficit was recorded, but the price paid was retrenchments and lean public spending.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Wine and copper were the only industries not to suffer a downturn.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Adelaide was Australia's third largest city for most of the 20th century.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Electric street lighting was introduced in 1900 and electric trams were transporting passengers in 1909.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] 28,000 men were sent to fight in World War I.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Crowley examined the reports of visitors in the early 20th century, noting that "many visitors to Adelaide admired the foresighted planning of its founders", as well as pondering the riches of the young city.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Adelaide enjoyed a postwar boom, entering a time of relative prosperity.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Its population grew, and it became the third most populous metropolitan area in the country, after Sydney and Melbourne.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Its prosperity was short-lived, with the return of droughts and the Great Depression of the 1930s.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] It later returned to fortune under strong government leadership.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Secondary industries helped reduce the state's dependence on primary industries.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] World War II brought industrial stimulus and diversification to Adelaide under the Playford Government, which advocated Adelaide as a safe place for manufacturing due to its less vulnerable location.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Shipbuilding was expanded at the nearby port of Whyalla.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The South Australian Government in this period built on former wartime manufacturing industries but neglected cultural facilities which meant South Australia's economy lagged behind.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] International manufacturers like Holden and Chrysler made use of these factories around the Adelaide area in suburbs like Elizabeth, completing its transformation from an agricultural service centre to a 20th-century motor city.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The Mannum–Adelaide pipeline brought River Murray water to Adelaide in 1955 and an airport opened at West Beach in 1955.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Flinders University and the Flinders Medical Centre were established in the 1960s at Bedford Park, south of the city.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Today, Flinders Medical Centre is one of the largest teaching hospitals in South Australia.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] In the post-war years around the early 1960s, Adelaide was surpassed by Brisbane as Australia's third largest city.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The Dunstan Governments of the 1970s saw something of an Adelaide "cultural revival", establishing a wide array of social reforms.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The city became noted for its progressivism as South Australia became the first Australian state or territory to decriminalise homosexuality between consenting adults in 1975.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Adelaide became a centre for the arts, building upon the biennial "Adelaide Festival of Arts" that commenced in 1960.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The State Bank collapsed in 1991 during an economic recession.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The effects lasted until 2004, when Standard & Poor's reinstated South Australia's AAA credit rating.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's tallest building, completed in 2020, is called the Adelaidean and is located at 11 Frome Street.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] In the early years of the 21st century, a significant increase in the state government's spending on Adelaide's infrastructure occurred.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The Rann government invested A$535 million in a major upgrade of the Adelaide Oval to enable Australian Football League to be played in the city centre and more than A$2 billion to build a new Royal Adelaide Hospital on land adjacent to the Adelaide Railway Station.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The Glenelg tramline was extended through the city to Hindmarsh down to East Terrace and the suburban railway line extended south to Seaford.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Following a period of stagnation in the 1990s and 2000s, Adelaide began several major developments and redevelopments.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The Adelaide Convention Centre was redeveloped and expanded at a cost of A$350 million beginning in 2012.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The government invested more than A$2 billion to build a desalination plant, powered by renewable energy, as an "insurance policy" against droughts affecting Adelaide's water supply.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The Adelaide Festival, Fringe, and Womadelaide became annual events.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is north of the Fleurieu Peninsula, on the Adelaide Plains between the Gulf St Vincent and the relatively low-lying Mount Lofty Ranges (Mount Lofty, the highest point, is 710 metres above sea level).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The city stretches 20 km (12 mi) from the coast to the foothills, and 90 km (56 mi) from Gawler at its northern extent to Sellicks Beach in the south.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The city sits at an average elevation of 50 metres (160 ft) above sea level.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Mount Lofty, east of the Adelaide metropolitan region in the Adelaide Hills at an elevation of 727 metres (2,385 ft), is the tallest point of the city and in the state south of Burra.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The city borders the Temperate Grassland of South Australia in the east, an endangered vegetation community.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Much of Adelaide was bushland before British settlement, with some variation – sandhills, swamps and marshlands were prevalent around the coast.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The loss of the sandhills to urban development had a particularly destructive effect on the coastline due to erosion.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Where practical, the government has implemented programs to rebuild and vegetate sandhills at several of Adelaide's beachside suburbs.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Tennyson Dunes is the largest contiguous, tertiary dune system contained entirely within Metropolitan Adelaide, providing refuge for a variety of remnant species formerly found along the entire coastline.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Much of the original vegetation has been cleared with what is left to be found in reserves such as the Cleland National Park and Belair National Park.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] A number of creeks and rivers flow through the Adelaide region.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The largest are the Torrens and Onkaparinga catchments.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Adelaide relies on its many reservoirs for water supply with the Happy Valley Reservoir supplying around 40% and the much larger Mount Bold Reservoir 10% of Adelaide's domestic requirements respectively.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Adelaide and its surrounding area is one of the most seismically active regions in Australia.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] On 1 March 1954 at 3:40 am Adelaide experienced its largest recorded earthquake to date, with the epicentre 12 km from the city centre at Darlington, and a reported magnitude of 5.6.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Most of the Adelaide metropolitan area lies in the downthrown St Vincent Basin and its embayments, including the Adelaide Plains Sub-basin, and the Golden Grove, Noarlunga and Willunga Embayments.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] These basins contain deposits of Tertiary marine and non-marine sands and limestones, which form important aquifers.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is a planned city, designed by the first Surveyor-General of South Australia, Colonel William Light.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] His plan, sometimes referred to as "Light's Vision" (also the name of a statue of him on Montefiore Hill), arranged Adelaide in a grid, with five squares in the Adelaide city centre and a ring of parks, known as the Adelaide Parklands, surrounding it.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Light's selection of the location for the city was initially unpopular with the early settlers, as well as South Australia's first governor, John Hindmarsh, due to its distance from the harbour at Port Adelaide, and the lack of fresh water there.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Light successfully persisted with his choice of location against this initial opposition.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The benefits of Light's design are numerous: Adelaide has had wide multi-lane roads from its beginning, an easily navigable cardinal direction grid layout and an expansive green ring around the city centre.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] There are two sets of ring roads in Adelaide that have resulted from the original design.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The inner ring route (A21) borders the parklands, and the outer route (A3/A13/A16/A17) completely bypasses the inner city via (in clockwise order) Grand Junction Road, Hampstead Road, Ascot Avenue, Portrush Road, Cross Road and South Road.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Suburban expansion has to some extent outgrown Light's original plan.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Numerous former outlying villages and "country towns", as well as the satellite city of Elizabeth, have been enveloped by its suburban sprawl.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Expanding developments in the Adelaide Hills region led to the construction of the South Eastern Freeway to cope with growth, which has subsequently led to new developments and further improvements to that transport corridor.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Similarly, the booming development in Adelaide's South led to the construction of the Southern Expressway.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] New roads are not the only transport infrastructure developed to cope with the urban growth.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The O-Bahn Busway and Adelaide Metro are examples of a unique solution to Tea Tree Gully's transport woes in the 1980s.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The development of the nearby suburb of Golden Grove in the late 1980s followed a planned approach to urban growth.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] In the 1960s, a Metropolitan Adelaide Transport Study Plan was proposed to cater for the future growth of the city.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The plan involved the construction of freeways, expressways and the upgrade of certain aspects of the public transport system.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The then premier Steele Hall approved many parts of the plan and the government went as far as purchasing land for the project.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The later Labor government elected under Don Dunstan shelved the plan, but allowed the purchased land to remain vacant, should the future need for freeways arise.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] In 1980, the Liberal party won government and premier David Tonkin committed his government to selling off the land acquired for the MATS plan, ensuring that even when needs changed, the construction of most MATS-proposed freeways would be impractical.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Some parts of this land have been used for transport, (e.g. the O-Bahn Busway and Southern Expressway), while most has been progressively subdivided for residential use.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] In 2008, the SA Government announced plans for a network of transport-oriented developments across the Adelaide metropolitan area and purchased a 10 hectare industrial site at Bowden for $52.5 million as the first of these developments.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Historically, Adelaide's suburban residential areas have been characterised by single-storey detached houses built on 1,000-square-metre (1⁄4-acre) blocks.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] A relative lack of suitable, locally available timber for construction purposes led to the early development of a brick-making industry, as well as the use of stone, for houses and other buildings.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] By 1891, 68% of houses were built of stone, 15% of timber, and 10% of brick, with brick also being widely used in stone houses for quoins, door and window surrounds, and chimneys and fireplaces.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] There is a wide variety in the styles of these houses.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Until the 1960s, most of the more substantial houses were built of red brick, though many front walls were of ornamental stone.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Then cream bricks became fashionable, and in the 1970s, deep red and brown bricks became popular.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Until the 1970s, roofs tended to be clad with (painted) corrugated iron or cement or clay tiles, usually red "terracotta".
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Since then, Colorbond corrugated steel has dominated.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Up to the 1970s, most houses were of "double brick" construction on concrete footings, with timber floors laid on joists supported by "dwarf walls".
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The use of precast concrete panels for floor and wall construction has also increased.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] In addition to this, a significant factor in Adelaide's suburban history is the role of the South Australian Housing Trust.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Adelaide has a hot-summer Mediterranean climate (*Csa*) under the Köppen climate classification.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The city has hot, dry summers and cool winters with moderate rainfall.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Most rain falls in the winter months, leading to the suggestion that the climate be classified as a "cold monsoon".
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Rainfall is unreliable, light and infrequent throughout summer, although heavy falls can occur.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The winter has fairly reliable rainfall with June being the wettest month of the year, averaging around 80 mm.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Frosts are occasional, with the most notable occurrences in 1908 and 1982.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is a windy city with significant wind chill in winter, which makes the temperature seem colder than it actually is.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Snowfall in the metropolitan area is extremely rare, although light and sporadic falls in the nearby hills and at Mount Lofty occur during winter.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Dewpoints in the summer typically range from 8 to 10 °C (46 to 50 °F).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] There are usually several days in summer where the temperature reaches 40.0 °C (104.0 °F) or above.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] While conditions vary from year-to-year, a warming trend has been increasing in recent years, and with drought conditions experienced in SA in 2024−25, Adelaide has had to rely on desalination to augment its water supply.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The city features 90.6 clear days annually.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The average sea temperature ranges from 13.7 °C (56.7 °F) in August to 21.2 °C (70.2 °F) in February.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Adelaide was consistently ranked in the world's 10 most liveable cities through the 2010s by The Economist Intelligence Unit.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] In June 2021, *The Economist* ranked Adelaide the third most liveable city in the world, behind Auckland and Osaka.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] In June 2023, Adelaide was ranked the twelfth most liveable city in the world by the Economist Intelligence Unit.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] In December 2021, Adelaide was named the world's second National Park City, after the state government had lobbied for this title.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] It was ranked the most liveable city in Australia by the Property Council of Australia, based on surveys of residents' views of their own city, between 2010 and 2013, dropping to second place in 2014.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Adelaide, as the capital of South Australia, is the seat of the Government of South Australia.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The bicameral Parliament of South Australia consists of the lower house known as the House of Assembly and the upper house known as the Legislative Council.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] General elections are held every four years, the last being the 2022 South Australian state election.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] As Adelaide is South Australia's capital and most populous city, the State Government co-operates extensively with the City of Adelaide.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] In 2006, the Ministry for the City of Adelaide was created to facilitate the State Government's collaboration with the Adelaide City Council and the Lord Mayor to improve Adelaide's image.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The State Parliament's Capital City Committee is also involved in the governance of the City of Adelaide, being primarily concerned with the planning of Adelaide's urban development and growth.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Reflecting South Australia's status as Australia's most centralised state, Adelaide elects a substantial majority of the South Australian House of Assembly.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Of the 47 seats in the chamber, 34 seats (three-quarters of the legislature) are based in Adelaide, and two rural seats include Adelaide suburbs.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The Adelaide metropolitan area is divided between nineteen local government areas.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] At its centre, the City of Adelaide administers the Adelaide city centre, North Adelaide, and the surrounding Adelaide Parklands.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] It is the oldest municipal authority in Australia and was established in 1840, when Adelaide and Australia's first mayor, James Hurtle Fisher, was elected.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] From 1919 onwards, the city has had a Lord Mayor, the current being Lord Mayor *The Right Honourable* Jane Lomax-Smith.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's inhabitants are known as Adelaideans.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Compared with Australia's other state capitals, Adelaide is growing at a rate similar to Sydney and Hobart (see List of cities in Australia by population).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] In 2024, it had a metropolitan population (including suburbs) of 1,469,163, making it Australia's fifth-largest city.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] 77% of the population of South Australia are residents of the Adelaide metropolitan area, making South Australia one of the most centralised states.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Major areas of population growth in recent years have been in outer suburbs such as Mawson Lakes and Golden Grove.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's inhabitants occupy 366,912 houses, 57,695 semi-detached, row terrace or town houses and 49,413 flats, units or apartments.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] About one sixth (17.1%) of the population had university qualifications.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The number of Adelaideans with vocational qualifications (such as tradespersons) fell from 62.1% of the labour force in the 1991 census to 52.4% in the 2001 census.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is aging more rapidly than other Australian capital cities.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] More than a quarter (27.5%) of Adelaide's population is aged 55 years or older, in comparison to the national average of 25.6%.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Adelaide has the lowest number of children (under-15-year-olds), who comprised 17.7% of the population, compared to the national average of 19.3%.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Overseas-born Adelaideans composed 31.3% of the total population at the 2021 census.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The five largest groups of overseas-born were from England (5.7%), India (3.1%), Mainland China (1.8%), Vietnam (1.2%) and Italy (1.1%).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Suburbs including Newton, Payneham and Campbelltown in the east and Torrensville, West Lakes and Fulham to the west, have large Greek and Italian communities.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The Italian consulate is located in the western suburb of Hindmarsh.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Large Vietnamese populations are settled in the north-western suburbs of Woodville, Kilkenny, Pennington, Mansfield Park and Athol Park and also Parafield Gardens and Pooraka in Adelaide's north.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Migrants from India and Sri Lanka have settled into inner suburban areas of Adelaide including the inner northern suburbs of Blair Athol, Kilburn and Enfield and the inner southern suburbs of Plympton, Park Holme and Kurralta Park.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Suburbs such as Para Hills, Salisbury, Ingle Farm and Blair Athol in the north and Findon, West Croydon and Seaton and other Western suburbs have sizeable Afghan communities.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Chinese migrants favour settling in the eastern and north eastern suburbs including Kensington Gardens, Greenacres, Modbury and Golden Grove.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Mawson Lakes has a large international student population, due to its proximity to the University of South Australia campus.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] At the 2021 census, 1.7% of Adelaide's population identified as being Indigenous — Aboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islanders.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] At the 2016 census, 75.4% of the population spoke English at home.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The other languages most commonly spoken at home were Italian (2.1%), Standard Mandarin (2.1%), Greek (1.7%) Vietnamese (1.4%), and Cantonese (0.7%).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The Kaurna language, spoken by the area's original inhabitants, had no living speakers in the middle of the 20th century, but since the 1990s there has been a sustained revival effort from academics and Kaurna elders.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Adelaide was founded on a vision of religious tolerance that attracted a wide variety of religious practitioners.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] This led to it being known as *The City of Churches*.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] But approximately 28% of the population expressed no religious affiliation in the 2011 Census, compared with the national average of 22.3%, making Adelaide one of Australia's least religious cities.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] According to 2021 census, 39.8% of the population of Adelaide identify as Christian, with the largest denominations being Catholic (16.4%), Anglican (7.0%), Uniting Church (3.9%) and Greek Orthodox (2.4%).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Non-Christian faith communities, representing 9.5% from Adelaide's population, include Islam (2.8%), Hinduism (2.7%) and Buddhism (2.3%).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The Jewish community of the city dates back to 1840.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Eight years later, 58 Jews lived in the city.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] A synagogue was built in 1871, when 435 Jews lived in the city.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Many took part in the city councils, such as Judah Moss Solomon (1852–66).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Three Jews have been elected to the position of city mayor.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] In 1968, the Jewish population of Adelaide numbered about 1,200; in 2001, according to the Australian census, 979 persons declared themselves to be Jewish by religion.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] In 2011, over 1,000 Jews were living in the city, served by an Orthodox synagogue, Adelaide Hebrew Congregation and a Reform synagogue, **Beit Shalom**, in addition to a virtual Jewish museum.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Massada College, a Jewish day school opened in the city in 1976 and closed in 2011.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The Adelaide Holocaust Museum and Andrew Steiner Education Centre opened in 2020.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The "Afghan" community in Australia first became established in the 1860s when camels and their Pathan, Punjabi, Baluchi and Sindhi handlers began to be used to open up settlement in the continent's arid interior.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Until eventually superseded by the advent of the railways and motor vehicles, camels played an invaluable economic and social role in transporting heavy loads of goods to and from isolated settlements and mines.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] This is acknowledged by the name of The Ghan, the passenger train operating between Adelaide, Alice Springs, and Darwin.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The Central Adelaide Mosque is regarded as Australia's oldest permanent mosque; an earlier mosque at Marree in northern South Australia, dating from 1861 to 1862 and subsequently abandoned or demolished, has now been rebuilt.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] South Australia's largest employment sectors are health care and social assistance, surpassing manufacturing in SA as the largest employer since 2006–07.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] In 2009–10, manufacturing in SA had average annual employment of 83,700 persons compared with 103,300 for health care and social assistance.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Health care and social assistance represented nearly 13% of the state average annual employment.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The Adelaide Hills wine region is an iconic and viable economic region for both the state and country in terms of wine production and sale.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The retail trade is the second largest employer in SA (2009–10), with over 91,900 jobs, and 12 per cent of the state workforce.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Manufacturing, defence technology, high-tech electronic systems and research, commodity export and corresponding service industries all play a role in the SA economy.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Almost half of all cars produced in Australia were made in Adelaide at the Holden Elizabeth Plant in Elizabeth.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The site ceased operating in November 2017.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The collapse of the State Bank in 1992 resulted in large levels of state public debt (as much as A$4 billion).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The collapse meant that successive governments enacted lean budgets, cutting spending, which was a setback to the further economic development of the city and state.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] As of January 2026, the government has an AA+ credit rating.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The global media conglomerate News Corporation was founded in, and until 2004 incorporated in, Adelaide, and the city is still considered the Corporation's "spiritual" home by its founder, Rupert Murdoch.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Australia's largest oil company, Santos, prominent South Australian brewery, Coopers, and national retailer Harris Scarfe also call Adelaide their home.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] In 2018, at which time more than 80 organisations employed 800 people in the space sector in South Australia, Adelaide was chosen for the headquarters of a new Australian Space Agency.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] It is working to triple the size of the Australian space industry and create 20,000 new jobs by 2030.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is home to a large proportion of Australia's defence industries, which contribute over A$1 billion to South Australia's Gross State Product.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Others, such as Saab Systems and Raytheon, are in or near Technology Park.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] ASC Pty Ltd, is based in the industrial suburb of Osborne and is also a part of Technology Park.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] South Australia was charged with constructing Australia's *Collins*-class submarines and more recently the A$6 billion contract to construct the Royal Australian Navy's new air-warfare destroyers.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] As of November 2015, Greater Adelaide had an unemployment rate of 7.4% with a youth unemployment rate of 15%.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The median weekly individual income for people aged 15 years and over was $447 per week in 2006, compared with $466 nationally.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The median family income was $1,137 per week, compared with $1,171 nationally.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's housing and living costs are substantially lower than that of other Australian cities, with housing being notably cheaper.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The median Adelaide house price is half that of Sydney and two-thirds that of Melbourne.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The three-month trend unemployment rate to March 2007 was 6.2%.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] The Northern suburbs' unemployment rate is disproportionately higher than the other regions of Adelaide at 8.3%, while the East and South are lower than the Adelaide average at 4.9% and 5.0% respectively.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Over the decade March 2001 – March 2010, Metropolitan Adelaide median house prices approximately tripled.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] 11%p.a. compounding) In the five years March 2007 – March 2012, prices increased by approx.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] March 2012 – March 2017 saw a further increase of 19% – approx.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] no longer release a median house price for the Adelaide Metropolitan area, so figures retrieved are from Dept of the Premier and Cabinet.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Each quarter, The Alternative and Direct Investment Securities Association (ADISA) publishes a list of median house sale prices by suburb and Local Government Area.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p01] Quarterly Reports for the last two years can be found on the REISA website.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Education forms an increasingly important part of the city's economy, with the South Australian Government and educational institutions attempting to position Adelaide as "Australia's education hub" and marketing it as a "Learning City".
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The number of international students studying in Adelaide has increased rapidly in recent years to 30,726 in 2015, of which 1,824 were secondary school students.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Adelaide is the birthplace of three Nobel laureates, more than any other Australian city: physicist William Lawrence Bragg and pathologists Howard Florey and Robin Warren, all of whom completed secondary and tertiary education at St Peter's College and the University of Adelaide.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Adelaide is also the hometown of mathematician Terence Tao.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] There are two systems of primary and secondary schools, a public system operated by the South Australian Government's Department for Education, and a private system of independent and Catholic schools.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] South Australian schools provide education under the Australian Curriculum for reception to Year 10 students.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] In Years 10 to 12, students study for the South Australian Certificate of Education (SACE).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] They have the option of incorporating vocational education and training (VET) courses or a flexible learning option (FLO).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] South Australia also has 24 schools that use International Baccalaureate programs as an alternative to the Australian Curriculum or SACE.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] These programs include the IB Primary Years Programme, the IB Middle Years Programme, and the IB Diploma Programme.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] For South Australian students who cannot attend a traditional school, including students who live in rural or remote areas, the state government runs the Open Access College (OAC), which provides virtual teaching.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The OAC has a campus in Marden which caters to students from reception to Year 12 and adults who haven't been able to complete their SACE.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Guardians are also able to apply for their child to be educated from home as long as they provide an education program which meets the same requirements as the Australian Curriculum as well as opportunities for social interaction.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] There are two public universities local to Adelaide, as well as one private university and three constituent colleges of foreign universities.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Flinders University of South Australia, Adelaide University and Torrens University Australia—part of the Laureate International Universities are based in Adelaide.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The University of Adelaide was ranked in the top 150 universities worldwide.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Flinders ranked in the top 250 and Uni SA in the top 300.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Torrens University Australia is part of an international network of over 70 higher education institutions in more than 30 countries worldwide.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Adelaide University is a recent amalgamation between the University of Adelaide and the University of South Australia, ranked in the top 150 globally and top 10 nationally.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Today, it stands as Australia's third-oldest university and a member of the leading "Group of Eight".
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The merged university has over 64,000 students and two main campuses on North Terrace, with many other campuses across South Australia, including in Whyalla and Mount Gambier.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The two universities had multiple proposals to merge into a single university.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] A proposal in 2018 failed due to uncertainty as to the new name and leadership of the merged university.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] In 2022, the universities announced a new merger proposal, with the name and leadership issues settled and support from the South Australian government.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Flinders University, with 25,184 students, is based in the southern suburb of Bedford Park, alongside the Flinders Medical Centre, with additional campuses in neighbouring Tonsley and in Victoria Square in the city centre.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] In 2024, the University of the Sunshine Coast opened a new campus in Adelaide where undergraduate and master's courses in ICT and business are offered.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide College of Divinity is at Brooklyn Park.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] There are several South Australian TAFE (Technical and Further Education) campuses in the metropolitan area that provide a range of vocational education and training.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide College of the Arts, as a school of TAFE SA, provides nationally recognised training in visual and performing arts.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The Workers' Educational Association of South Australia (WEA-SA) is an independent not-for-profit adult education organisation based in Adelaide.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Established in 1913, it is one of Australia's longest running providers of community-based adult learning.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] WEA-SA delivers short courses, lectures, cultural programs, travel and interest clubs designed to promote lifelong learning.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] StudyAdelaide, a collaboration between the South Australian government and the tertiary education sector, maintains an on-line list of schools, universities, and higher education institutions in SA.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] In addition to the universities, Adelaide is home to research institutes, including the Royal Institution of Australia, established in 2009 as a counterpart to the two-hundred-year-old Royal Institution of Great Britain.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] While established as a British province, and very much English in terms of its culture, Adelaide attracted immigrants from other parts of Europe early on, including German and other European non-conformists escaping religious persecution.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The first German Lutherans arrived in 1838, bringing with them the vine cuttings that they used to found the acclaimed wineries of the Barossa Valley.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The Royal Adelaide Show is an annual agricultural show and state fair, established in 1839 and now a huge event held in the Adelaide Showground annually.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's arts scene flourished in the 1960s and 1970s with the support of successive premiers from both major political parties.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The renowned Adelaide Festival of Arts was established in 1960 under Thomas Playford, which in the same year spawned an unofficial uncurated series of performances and exhibits which grew into the Adelaide Fringe.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Construction of the Adelaide Festival Centre began under Steele Hall in 1970 and was completed under the subsequent government of Don Dunstan, who also established the South Australian Film Corporation in 1972 and the State Opera of South Australia in 1976.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] With the Festival, the Fringe, WOMADelaide, Writers' Week and the Adelaide 500 street motor racing event (along with evening music concerts) all happening in early March, the period became known colloquially as "Mad March".
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] In 2014, Ghil'ad Zuckermann founded the Adelaide Language Festival.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] There are many international cultural fairs, most notably the German Schützenfest and Greek Glendi.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Adelaide holds an annual Christmas pageant, the world's largest Christmas parade.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] As the state capital, Adelaide has a great number of cultural institutions, many of them along the boulevard of North Terrace.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The Art Gallery of South Australia, with about 35,000 works, holds Australia's second largest state-based collection.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Adjacent are the South Australian Museum and State Library of South Australia.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide Botanic Garden, National Wine Centre and Tandanya National Aboriginal Cultural Institute are nearby in the East End of the city.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] In the back of the State Library lies the Migration Museum, Australia's oldest museum of its kind.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Further west, the Lion Arts Centre is home to ACE Open, which showcases contemporary art; Dance Hub SA; and other studios and arts industry spaces.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The Mercury Cinema and the JamFactory ceramics and design gallery are just around the corner.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide Festival Centre (which includes the Dunstan Playhouse, Festival Theatre and Space Theatre), on the banks of the Torrens, is the focal point for much of the cultural activity in the city and home to the State Theatre Company of South Australia.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Other live music and theatre venues include the Adelaide Entertainment Centre; Adelaide Oval; Memorial Drive Park; Thebarton Theatre; Adelaide Town Hall; Her Majesty's Theatre; Queen's Theatre; Holden Street Theatres; and the Hopgood Theatre.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The Lion Arts Factory, within the Lion Arts Centre, hosts contemporary music in a wide range of genres, as does "The Gov" in Hindmarsh.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The city also has numerous smaller theatres, pubs and cabaret bars which host performances.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] In 2015, it was said that there were now more live music venues per capita in Adelaide than any other capital city in the southern hemisphere, *Lonely Planet* labelled Adelaide "Australia's live music city", and the city was recognised as a "City of Music" by the UNESCO Creative Cities Network.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Although there were many pubs hosting live music in the CBD in past, the number has slowly diminished.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The Grace Emily on Waymouth Street, which was refurbished as a live music venue around 2000, is popular with musicians and patrons alike.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The Crown & Anchor ("the Cranker") was saved from demolition in 2024 after a vigorous campaign by the public as well as many musicians and politicians.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] New legislation passed on 11 September 2024 designates the entire Adelaide CBD as a "live music venue area", and gives protection to selected live music venues.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] In addition to its own WOMAD (WOMADelaide), Adelaide has attracted several touring music festivals, including Creamfields, Laneway, and Groovin' (some since defunct).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Adelaide has produced musical groups and individuals who have achieved national and international fame.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Noted rocker Jimmy Barnes (formerly lead vocalist with Cold Chisel) spent most of his youth in the northern suburb of Elizabeth.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Australian singer-songwriter Paul Kelly grew up in Adelaide and was head prefect at Rostrevor College.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The first *Australian Idol* winner, Guy Sebastian, hails from the north-eastern suburb of Golden Grove.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] All of the five Australian national television networks broadcast both high-definition digital and standard-definition digital television services in Adelaide.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] They share three transmission towers on the ridge near the summit of Mount Lofty.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] There are two other transmission sites at 25 Grenfell Street, Adelaide and Elizabeth Downs.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The two government-funded stations are run by the Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC South Australia) and the Special Broadcasting Service (SBS).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The Seven Network and Network Ten both own their Adelaide stations (SAS-7 and ADS-10 respectively).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's NWS-9 is part of the Nine Network.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Adelaide also has a community television station, Channel 44.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] As part of a nationwide phase-out of analogue television in Australia, Adelaide's analogue television service was shut down on 2 April 2013.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] There are 20 radio stations that serve the metropolitan area, as well as four stations that serve only parts of the metropolitan area; six commercial stations, six community stations, six national stations and two narrowcast stations.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] DAB+ digital radio has been broadcasting in metropolitan Adelaide since 20 May 2009, and currently offers a choice of 41 stations all operated by the existing licensed radio broadcasters, which includes high-quality simulcast of all AM and FM stations.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The main sports played professionally in Adelaide are Australian Rules football, soccer, cricket, netball, and basketball.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Adelaide is the home of two Australian Football League teams: the Adelaide Football Club and Port Adelaide Football Club, and one A-League soccer team, Adelaide United.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] A local Australian rules football league, the South Australian National Football League (SANFL), is made up of 10 teams from around Adelaide.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The SANFL has been in operation since 1877 when it began as the South Australian Football Association (SAFA) before changing its name to the SANFL in 1927.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The SANFL is the oldest surviving football league of any code played in Australia.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Since completion of the upgrade, home games for Adelaide Crows and Port Adelaide now take place at Adelaide Oval.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Since 1884, Adelaide Oval has also hosted an international cricket test every summer, along with a number of One Day International cricket matches.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Memorial Drive Park, adjacent to the Adelaide Oval, used to host Davis Cup and other major tennis events, including the Australian Open and the Adelaide International.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's professional association football team, Adelaide United, play in the A-League.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Founded in 2003, their home ground is Coopers Stadium, which has a capacity of 16,500 and is one of the few purpose-built soccer stadia in Australia.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Prior to United's foundation, Adelaide City and West Adelaide represented the city in the National Soccer League.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The two sides, which contest the Adelaide derby against one another, now play in the National Premier Leagues South Australia.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] For two years, 1997 and 1998, Adelaide was represented in Australia's top level rugby league, after the New South Wales Rugby League had played a single game per season at the Adelaide Oval for five years starting in 1991.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide Rams were formed and played in the breakaway Super League (SL) competition in 1997 before moving to the new National Rugby League in 1998.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Initially playing at the Adelaide Oval, the club moved to the more suitable Hindmarsh Stadium late in the 1998 season.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] As part of a peace deal with the Australian Rugby League to end the Super League war, the club's owners News Limited (who were also owners of the SL) suddenly closed the club only weeks before the start of the 1999 season.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Adelaide has two professional basketball teams, the men's team being the Adelaide 36ers which plays in the National Basketball League (NBL) and the women's team, the Adelaide Lightning which plays in the Women's National Basketball League (WNBL).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide 36ers play at the Adelaide Entertainment Centre while the Adelaide Lightning play at the Adelaide Arena (Previously Titanium Security Arena).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Adelaide has a professional netball team, the Adelaide Thunderbirds, which plays in the national netball competition, the Super Netball championship, with home games played at Netball SA Stadium.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The Thunderbirds occasionally play games or finals at the Titanium Security Arena, while international netball matches are usually played at the 10,500 seat Adelaide Entertainment Centre.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The Titanium Security Arena has a capacity of 8,000 and is the largest purpose-built basketball stadium in Australia.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Since 1999 Adelaide and its surrounding areas have hosted the Tour Down Under bicycle race, organised and directed by Adelaide-based Michael Turtur.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Turtur won an Olympic gold medal for Australia in the 4000 m team pursuit at the 1984 Los Angeles Olympics.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The Tour Down Under is the largest cycling event outside Europe and was the first event outside Europe to be granted UCI ProTour status.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The 2024 Women's Tour Down Under cycle stage race was held in and around Adelaide, South Australia from 12 to 14 January 2024.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Adelaide maintains a franchise in the Australian Baseball League, the Adelaide Giants.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] They have been playing since 2009, and their home stadium (until 2016) was Norwood Oval.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] From 2016 the team moved to the Diamond Sports Stadium located near the Adelaide International Airport due to renovations at Norwood.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Adelaide also has an ice hockey team, Adelaide Adrenaline in the Australian Ice Hockey League (AIHL).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] It was national champions in 2009 and plays its games at the IceArenA.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The Australian Grand Prix for World Championship Formula One racing was hosted by Adelaide from 1985 to 1995 on the Adelaide Street Circuit which was laid out in the city's East End as well as the eastern parklands including the Victoria Park Racecourse.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The Grand Prix became a source of pride, and losing the event to Melbourne in a surprise announcement in mid-1993 left a void that has since been filled with the Adelaide 500 for V8 Supercar racing, held on a modified version of the same street circuit.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The Classic Adelaide, a rally of classic sporting vehicles, is also held in the city and its surrounds.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Adelaide formerly had three horse racing venues.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Victoria Park, Cheltenham Park Racecourse, both of which have now closed, and Morphettville Racecourse that remains the home of the South Australian Jockey Club.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] It also has Globe Derby Park for Harness racing that opened in 1969, and by 1973 had become Adelaide's premier harness racing venue taking over from the Wayville Showgrounds, as well as Greyhound Park for greyhound racing that opened in 1972.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The World Solar Challenge race attracts teams from around the world, most of which are fielded by universities or corporations, although some are fielded by high schools.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The race has a 20-years' history spanning nine races, with the inaugural event taking place in 1987.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Adelaide hosted the 2012 World Bowls Championships at Lockleys Bowling Club, becoming the third city in the world to have held the championships twice, having previously hosted the event in 1996.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Dirt track speedway is also popular in Adelaide with three operating speedways.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Adelaide Motorsport Park, located adjacent to the Adelaide International Raceway road racing circuit at Virginia (24 km (15 mi) north of the city centre) has been in continuous operation since 1979 after the closure of the popular Rowley Park Speedway.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Gillman Speedway located in the semi-industrial suburb of Gillman, has been in operation since 1998 and caters to Motorcycle speedway and Sidecars, while the Sidewinders Speedway located in Wingfield is also a motorcycle speedway dedicated to Under-16 riders and has been in operation since 1978.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] In 2016, backed by South Australia's Peregrine Corporation opened up a multi-purpose facility; a state-of-the-art motorsporting park and a hotel alongside its newer OTR service station outside a small township of Tailem Bend currently named The Bend Motorsport Park.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Design for thrill seekers and rev-heads the facility currently host South Australia's second Supercars motoring event during a round in August.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Adelaide is home to the Great Southern Slam, the world's largest roller derby tournament.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The tournament has been held biennially over Australia's Queen's Birthday holiday weekend since 2010.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] In 2014, and 2016 the tournament featured 45 teams playing in two divisions.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] In 2018, the tournament has expanded to 48 teams competing in three divisions.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Being centrally located on the Australian mainland, Adelaide forms a strategic transport hub for east–west and north–south routes.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The city itself has a metropolitan public transport system managed by and known as the Adelaide Metro.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Tramways were largely dismantled in the 1950s, but saw a revival in the 2010s with upgrades and extensions.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Road transport in Adelaide has historically been easier than many of the other Australian cities, with a well-defined city layout and wide multiple-lane roads from the beginning of its development.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Adelaide was known as a "twenty-minute city", with commuters having been able to travel from metropolitan outskirts to the city proper in roughly twenty minutes.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] However, such arterial roads often experience traffic congestion as the city grows.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide metropolitan area has one freeway and four expressways.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide metropolitan area has two commercial airports, Adelaide Airport and Parafield Airport.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Adelaide Airport, in Adelaide's south-western suburbs, serves almost 9 million passengers annually, with an extensive number of direct flight routes within Australia, as well as other destinations in Oceania, Asia and North America.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Parafield Airport, Adelaide's second airport 18 kilometres (11 miles) north of the city centre, is used for small aircraft, pilot training and recreational aviation purposes.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Parafield Airport served as Adelaide's main aerodrome until the opening of the Adelaide Airport in February 1955.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Adelaide is also home to a military airport, known as RAAF Base Edinburgh, located in the northern suburbs.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] It was built in 1955 in a joint initiative with the United Kingdom for weapon development.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's two largest hospitals are the Royal Adelaide Hospital (RAH) in Adelaide Parklands, a teaching hospital affiliated with the University of Adelaide (800 beds), and the Flinders Medical Centre (580 beds) at Bedford Park, affiliated with Flinders University.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The RAH also operates additional campuses for specialist care throughout the suburbs including the Hampstead Rehabilitation Centre (150 beds) at Northfield and the Glenside Campus (129 beds) for acute mental health services.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Other major public hospitals are the Women's and Children's Hospital (305 beds), at North Adelaide; the Queen Elizabeth Hospital (340 beds) at Woodville; Modbury Hospital (174 beds) at Modbury; and the Lyell McEwin Hospital (198 beds) at Elizabeth Vale.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Numerous private hospitals are also located throughout the city, with the largest operators being not-for-profits Adelaide Community Healthcare Alliance (three hospitals) and Calvary Care (four hospitals).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] In 2017, the RAH was relocated from the city's East End to a new AU$2.3 billion facility built over former railyards in the West End.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] SAHMRI, with additional external funding, has built a $300 million second facility completed in 2024, which was intended to house the Australian Bragg Centre with Australia's first proton therapy unit.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Construction is underway for the Women's and Children's Hospital to be relocated to the precinct adjacent the RAH by 2030.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The largest provider of community health care within Adelaide is the not-for-profit Royal District Nursing Service, which provides out of hospital care and hospital avoidance care.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's energy requirements were originally met by the Adelaide Electric Supply Company, which was nationalised by the Playford government in 1946, becoming the Electricity Trust of South Australia (ETSA).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The electricity retail market was opened to competition in 2003 and although competition was expected to result in lower retail costs, prices increased by 23.7% in the market's first year.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] In 2004, the privatisation was deemed to be a failure with consumers paying 60% more for their power and with the state government estimated to lose $3 billion in power generation net income in the first ten years of privatisation.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] In 2012, the industry came under scrutiny for allegedly reducing supply by shutting down generators during periods of peak demand to force prices up.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Increased media attention also revealed that in 2009 the state government had approved a 46% increase in retail prices to cover expected increases in the costs of generation while generation costs had in fact fallen 35% by 2012.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] South Australia has the highest retail price for electricity in the country.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Privatisation led to competition from a variety of companies who now separately provide for the generation, transmission, distribution and retail sales of gas and electricity.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Electricity generation comes from a range of technologies and operators.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] ElectraNet operates the high-voltage electricity transmission network.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] SA Power Networks distributes electricity to end users.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The largest electricity and gas retailing companies are also the largest generating companies.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The largest fossil fuel power stations are the Torrens Island Power Station gas-fired plant operated by AGL Energy and the Pelican Point Power Station operated by Engie.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] South Australia also has wind and solar power and connections to the national grid.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Gas is supplied from the Moomba Gas Processing Plant in the Cooper Basin via the Moomba Adelaide Pipeline System and the SEAGas pipeline from Victoria.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] In 2011, South Australia generated 18% of its electricity from wind power, and had 51% of the installed capacity of wind generators in Australia.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Due to almost universal blackouts within the city during September 2016, the state worked with Tesla to produce the world's largest electricity battery at Hornsdale Power Reserve which has increased that state's electrical security to the extent in which large blackouts are no longer an event.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The provision of water services is by the government-owned SA Water.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's water is supplied from its seven reservoirs: Mount Bold, Happy Valley, Myponga, Millbrook, Hope Valley, Little Para and South Para.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The yield from these reservoir catchments can be as little as 10% of the city's requirements (90GL per annum) in drought years and about 60% in average years.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The remaining demand is met by the pumping of water from the River Murray.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] A sea-water desalination plant capable of supplying 100GL per annum was built during the 2001–2009 drought; however, it operated at about 8% of its capacity until 2019.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] In December 2018, the State and Federal Governments agreed to fund a $2m study to determine how the plant could be used to reduce reliance on river water, in an effort to help save the Murray River basin and mouth (including the Coorong) from further ecological damage.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] AdelaideFree WiFi is a citywide free Wi-Fi network covering most of the inner city areas of Adelaide, primarily the Adelaide CBD and Northern Adelaide precincts.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] It was officially launched at the Adelaide Central Markets on Tuesday 25 June 2014.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] It was originally provided by Internode with infrastructure provided by outdoor Cisco WiFi N access points attached to the top of lighting poles, as well as inside cafes and businesses across the city.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] In 2023, a new agreement was reached between the City of Adelaide and TPG Telecom to replace the network infrastructure, improving network speed and coverage.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The City of Adelaide, was a 10 sail composite (timber planking on a wrought-iron frame) clipper.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] It was rescued from the mooring where it sank, as HMS Carrick, in Glasgow in 1991.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] In 2001 it was decided that the ship's name would be reverted to the City of Adelaide, formally renamed in 2013, and arrived in Port Adelaide on 3 February 2014.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] It was not until June 2024 that the ship was moved from the barge Bradley by Wallbridge Gilbert Aztec (WGA) to the current home on Dock 2, as the centerpiece of a planned village in Port Adelaide's inner harbour.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The ship is owned by the Clipper Ship City of Adelaide Ltd (CSCOAL).
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The STV One and All, a 42-metre two-masted square-rigged brigantine and the ketch *The Failie* are moored at McLaren Wharf.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] The City of Adelaide has been involved in the sister cities movement since 1972.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] As of 2023 it has long-term international partnership arrangements with five cities, known as sister cities, based on formal agreements between Adelaide and each city.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adelaide-p02] This allows collaboration in the cultural, educational, business, and technical spheres.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] Greenwood's mother (now retired) was a dentist practising in Reigate, Surrey.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] Adrian Greenwood attended the Hawthorns School, Bletchingley, Surrey, an independent co-educational preparatory school (though at the time a boys-only boarding school), and then Tonbridge School, Kent, where his history teacher for A level was Dr (later Sir) Anthony Seldon.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] He read Philosophy, Politics and Economics (PPE) at Christ Church, Oxford before studying for an MBA at Imperial College, London.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] After leaving Imperial College, Greenwood began buying British Rail lost property – umbrellas, mobile phones, coats, and prams – and selling them at car boot sales around London.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] Then in 1998 he sent his first article to the *Antiques Bulletin*, and it was published.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] From then on he began writing for most of the British antiques and collectables magazines, as well as several interior design and heritage titles.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] You could go to an auction and buy a tea chest of books for £10, and then put them online for £10 each.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] Among Greenwood's specialities were Harry Potter books, leading, on one occasion, to an argument with the series' author J.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] It was a drawing Rowling had done of a little boy.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] Also there was a hand-coloured invitation to Rowling's daughter's 2nd birthday party (before Rowling's success, when she was living in Leith) and a list she had made of potential character names for the first Harry Potter book.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] When I put this on eBay, Rowling's literary agents demanded they be removed from sale due to 'breach of copyright.' I argued there was no breach of copyright if no pictures of the items appeared and so I sold them without images instead.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] In November 2010, one of Greenwood's first edition Harry Potter books was stolen from a gallery in Woodstock, a theft which caught the public imagination and was widely reported.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] After Greenwood appeared on ITV and BBC explaining how difficult the book would be to sell on, the thief panicked and abandoned the book in a carrier bag outside a branch of Boots in Abingdon.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] Greenwood diversified into taxidermy, classic cars, prints, maps, paintings and art, most notably works by Banksy.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] His sale of a safe by Banksy led to much press interest.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] He supplied items to a broad range of clients, including the British Library and the Getty Museum.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] In 2011, Greenwood retired from dealing to concentrate on writing.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] His first book, *Victoria's Scottish Lion*, a biography of Sir Colin Campbell, received very positive reviews.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] It is the first major biography of Campbell since 1880.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] "I first came across him 25 years ago when I was doing History 'A’ Level", explained Greenwood, "I couldn't understand why he wasn't more famous.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] Over the years I kept seeing his name in books on the Victorian army, by historians like Trevor Royle and Saul David, and he seemed by far the most brilliant general of his age, yet no one had looked at his career thoroughly for a century or more.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] Then, as I found out more about him, the idea of writing the story of this working class maverick, riling the Victorian establishment, became irresistible.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] While researching Campbell, Greenwood discovered a series of letters from Peninsular War officer, Lt Peter Le Mesurier, spanning almost the whole of the conflict.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] Greenwood cited Corelli Barnett and Christopher Hibbert as stylistic influences, as historians who sought to bridge the gap between academia and popular history.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] "I get very tired with the old artificial distinction between academic books which have to be dull as ditchwater, and popular history which in striving to be exciting, fails to be accurate.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] Greenwood was last seen alive at the Sainsbury's supermarket in Oxford Road, Kidlington, on 5 April 2016.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] He was murdered the next day, and his body found by his cleaner at his home on Iffley Road the following day, 7 April.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] He was pronounced dead at the scene, and the cause of death was given as "multiple stab wounds" with more than 30.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] Police said that the attack probably happened in the hallway of his home, and that it was a "vicious and sustained attack".
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] They first arrested a 26-year-old man, but at that time they were still seeking the weapon used and were keeping an open mind as to motive.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] The arrested man was later released without charge.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] A first edition of the children's book *The Wind in the Willows*, still in its original dust-jacket and valued at £50,000, was missing.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] A second person, a 50-year-old Peterborough man, Michael Danaher, was subsequently arrested on 10 April on suspicion of murder.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] On 12 April 2016, Danaher was charged with murder, and remanded into custody the following day.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] He placed *The Wind in the Willows* for sale on eBay the day after Greenwood's murder.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] Danaher appeared in court on 15 April by video link to confirm his name, speaking from HM Prison Woodhill where he would remain until his next court appearance in July.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] Following a three-week trial, Danaher was found guilty at Oxford Crown Court and sentenced to life imprisonment of 34 years.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/adrian-greenwood] "*The Wind in the Willows* Murder", a documentary about the murder, aired on 19 July 2017 on Channel 4 as part of the *Catching a Killer* series.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aimable-pélissier] Pélissier was born at Maromme (*Seine Inférieure*), of a family of prosperous artisans, his father being employed in a powder-magazine.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aimable-pélissier] After attending the military college of La Flèche and the special school of St Cyr, he entered the army in 1815 as second-lieutenant in an artillery regiment.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aimable-pélissier] Brilliant examination results in 1819 secured his appointment to the staff.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aimable-pélissier] He served as *aide-de-camp* in the Spanish campaign of 1823, and in the Morea expedition 1828–1829.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aimable-pélissier] In 1830, he took part in the expedition to Algeria, and on his return was promoted to the rank of *chef d'escadron*.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aimable-pélissier] After some years of staff service in Paris, he was again sent to Algeria as chief of staff of the province of Oran with the rank of lieutenant-colonel, and remained there until the Crimean War, taking a leading part in many important operations.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aimable-pélissier] In 1852 he successfully commanded the Siege of Laghouat.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aimable-pélissier] After the battles of October and November 1854 before Sevastopol, Pélissier was sent to the Crimea, where on 16 May 1855 he succeeded Marshal Canrobert as commander-in-chief of the French forces before the Siege of Sevastopol.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aimable-pélissier] His command was marked by relentless pressure of the enemy and unalterable determination to conduct the campaign without interference from Paris.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aimable-pélissier] His perseverance was crowned with success in the storming of the Tower of Malakoff on 8 September which ended the Siege of Sevastopol, crowning the Anglo-French Crimean War against Russia with victory.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aimable-pélissier] From March 1858 to May 1859, he was French ambassador in London, but was recalled to take command of the army of observation on the Rhine.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aimable-pélissier] In the same year, he became Grand Chancellor of the Legion of Honour.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aimable-pélissier] In 1860, he was appointed Governor-General of unruly colony of Algeria.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aimable-pélissier] Pélissier died there in 1864, when the dukedom became extinct.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aimable-pélissier] In 1855, Stephen Glover wrote The Duke of Malakoff's March.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] In 1972, the garrison was the site of one of the worst UK mainland IRA attacks of the time when a car bomb was detonated outside the headquarters mess of 16 Parachute Brigade, killing seven and injuring nineteen.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] The Official IRA claimed responsibility, stating that the attack was in revenge for the shootings in Derry that came to be known as Bloody Sunday.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] Following the attack the Army took steps to secure the garrison by erecting security fences around most of the barracks and lines, as well as introducing armed security patrols.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] The garrison area covers approximately 200 hectares (490 acres) and its population is about 10,500.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] Adjacent to the military town is some 2,700 hectares (6,700 acres) of open military training area.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] Established in 1854, Aldershot has long been seen as the home of the British Army.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] The garrison was established when the War Department bought a large area of land near to the village of Aldershot, with the objective of establishing a permanent training camp for the British Army.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] Over time, this camp grew into a military town and continues to be used by the Army to the present day.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] Before the establishment of the 'Camp at Aldershot', the British Army did not have any single permanent camp for training troops on a large scale.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] Historically, troops had been stationed in long established garrisons, many of which could trace their histories back as mediaeval, or earlier, defensive positions.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] In 1852, following the death of The Iron Duke, a group of reformers, which included Prince Albert, forged an alliance that would seek to improve the training of the Army.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] In 1853, a summer camp was established at Chobham Common and two divisional size military exercises were conducted.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] Following the success of these manoeuvres, it was decided that a permanent camp was needed where such exercises could be regularly conducted.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] Initially, Reigate was selected as a location that was strategically sound, and close enough to London, to defend against invasion from across the English Channel.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] Despite its obvious advantages, Reigate was situated in prime agricultural land that would prove too expensive to purchase.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] Lord Hardinge suggested Aldershot Heath as the location for the new training area, as land was less expensive, but still close enough to the South Coast to defend London.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] In January 1854, the British Government's War Department purchased areas of heathland around the small village of Aldershot at £12 an acre.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] By 1861, around 8,000 acres had been purchased.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] Between 1854 and 1859, around 1,200 wooden huts were constructed by a local civilian contractor, at a cost of £100,263.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] Queen Victoria and Prince Albert showed a keen interest in the establishment and the development of Aldershot as a garrison town.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] In 1855, they had a wooden Royal Pavilion built, in which they would often stay when attending reviews of the Army.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] In 1860, Prince Albert established and endowed the Prince Consort's Library.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] After the Crimean War, a division of regular troops was permanently based at Aldershot, and 'the Division at Aldershot' (including artillery at Christchurch, Hampshire, and cavalry at Hounslow, Middlesex) became one of the most important home commands of the British Army.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] In January 1876 a *Mobilization Scheme for the forces in Great Britain and Ireland* was published, with the *Active Army* divided into eight army corps based on the major Commands and Districts.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] The 2nd Corps was headquartered at Aldershot.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] This scheme disappeared in 1881, when the districts were retitled 'District Commands', with Aldershot usually listed as IX or X.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] In 1898, (when Queen Victoria's son, the Duke of Connaught, was General Officer Commanding) Aldershot Command was ranked I on the list.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] From 1901 to 1908 Aldershot Command was given the additional title of I Army Corps.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] The garrison subsequently became seen as home to the British Army.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] This status has been reflected in the use of Aldershot as a headquarters for a variety of regional commands over the last 100 years.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] HQ Aldershot Command continued in existence until c.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] February 1941, when it was replaced by HQ Aldershot Area.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] In the late 1870s, it was decided that the original hutted camp needed to be replaced with some more permanent structures.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] When the wooden huts had been built in the 1850s, the contractor had guaranteed the huts for 13 years; in practice, many of those huts were still serving their purpose some 30 years later.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] In November 1881, the first steps were taken to convert the hutted camp into permanent barracks.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] At this time, the first two brick buildings were constructed in North Camp; this was quickly followed by the construction of a number of larger brick-built bungalows to replace the previous wooden designs.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] Government House was built as the garrison commander's house in 1883.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] Between 1889 and 1893, the remaining wooden buildings, in both North Camp and South Camp, were replaced by brick buildings.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] Major-General Sir Evelyn Wood had recently been appointed General Officer Commanding at Aldershot and was keen to push forward the building of the new accommodation.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] It was also, at his request, that a convention for naming the barracks was formulated.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] Wood advocated that the new barracks should all be named to commemorate famous British victories; initially this proposal met with some resistance, but was eventually adopted.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] The barracks in Stanhope Lines took names from the famous battles of the Napoleonic Wars and those in Marlborough Lines took names from Marlborough's campaigns.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] The Military Headquarters Building in Steeles Road was completed in 1895.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] Smith-Dorrien House, the local social facility for soldiers, was completed in 1909.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] The garrison used to be the corps headquarters for the Royal Corps of Transport and the Army Catering Corps; when these were merged into the Royal Logistic Corps in 1993, the corps headquarters moved to Deepcut Barracks.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] Today, the garrison is home to the headquarters of the Regional Command of the British Army, and is also the administrative base for 101st Operational Sustainment Brigade.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] The garrison plays host to around 70 military units and organisations.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] On 22 February 1972, Aldershot experienced one of the worst UK mainland IRA attacks of the time.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] Seven people, all civilian support staff, including cooks, cleaners, and a Catholic priest, were killed and 19 people were injured, in a car bomb attack on the 16th Parachute Brigade headquarters mess at Aldershot garrison.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] This blast was later claimed, by the Official IRA, as revenge for the shootings in Derry that came to be known as Bloody Sunday.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] Until then, the military town had been open-plan, but the attack led to immediate action to secure military property.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] A memorial stone was placed on the site of the bombing.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] Following Aldershot's establishment as a large permanent training camp in the 1850s, the military presence continued to grow.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] The garrison was divided into the North Camp and the South Camp, either side of the Basingstoke Canal.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] As more soldiers arrived, they were first housed in bell tents due to a shortage of permanent accommodation.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] Later, wooden huts were built, which were in turn replaced by brick built barracks in the 1890s.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] Much of the Victorian camp was demolished in the 1960s.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] Prior to 1890, Aldershot garrison lacked permanent accommodation to house the growing military presence.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] Following the Barracks Act 1890 (53 & 54 Vict. c.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] 25) North Camp was rebuilt with brick barracks named: Blenheim, Lille, Malplaquet, Oudenarde, Ramillies and Tournay.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] The new barracks were built by Henry Wells, a locally based building contractor.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] This group of barracks then became known as the Marlborough Lines.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] Today, the only surviving barracks of the Marlborough Lines group is Lille barracks.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] The Victorian buildings were largely demolished in 1958, and then rebuilt with more modern facilities, although the original officers' mess survives.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] North Camp station is the garrison's original railway station.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] The area known as South Camp was rebuilt at much the same time as North Camp.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] Construction was completed by the same local company responsible for Marlborough Lines.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] This phase of construction saw nine barracks built, namely: Albuhera, Barossa, Corunna, Gibraltar, Maida, Buller, Mandora and McGrigor barracks.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] This group of barracks became known as Stanhope Lines.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] Many of these brick-build Victorian barracks were demolished in the late 1960s, to make way for what is now Montgomery Lines.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] One of the Victorian barracks did survive.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] Montgomery Lines was completed in the 1970s and was built on the site of several barracks that formerly made up Stanhope Lines.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] Much of South Camp has now been redeveloped as part of the Aldershot Urban Extension.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] Today, the military town has a population of around 10,500.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] This consists of around 3,900 resident soldiers, some 1,000 transient military personnel on courses or sport, 770 MoD Civil Servants and some 5,000 service dependents.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] The garrison contains 2,145 Service Family Accommodation quarters.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] The rest of the garrison comprises barracks, the Aldershot Military Stadium, Queen's Parade playing fields, Garrison Sports Centre and the Aldershot Centre For Health, which is a joint MoD and local authority venture.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] The garrison is mostly centred around the crossroads that join Queen's Avenue and Alison's Road.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] The military town includes local landmarks such as the Aldershot Observatory, Wellington Statue, the RAMC Memorial, Aldershot Military Cemetery, the Royal Garrison Church and other churches.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] Adjacent to the military town is some 2,700 hectares of open military training area, which is open to the public when not in use for military purposes.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] The Aldershot Garrison is referenced in the first paragraph of Rudyard Kipling's poem *Gunga Din*.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] The 1893 Sherlock Holmes story "The Adventure of the Crooked Man" is set in Aldershot Camp.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/aldershot-garrison] Holmes and Watson investigate the death of an infantry officer in his home at the camp.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] Prince **Alexander Danilovich Menshikov** (Russian: Александр Данилович Меншиков; 16 November [O.S.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] 12 November] 1729) was a Russian soldier and statesman.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] His official titles included generalissimo, prince of the Russian Empire, duke of Izhora, prince of the Holy Roman Empire, and duke of Cosel.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] Rising from humble origins, he became a highly appreciated associate and friend of Tsar Peter the Great, leading to his rise as a prominent political and military figure in early 18th-century Russia.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] Following Peter's death, he was the *de facto* ruler of Russia from 1725 to 1727.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] The origins of his youth are not known for certain.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] His fine appearance and witty character caught the attention of Franz Lefort, Peter's first favourite, who took him into his service and finally transferred him to the Tsar.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] Massie states it was likely his father was an ex Lithuanian corporal-clark stationed in the Preobrazhenskoye District where his son was noticed and became a soldier in the Tsar's newly formed army units.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] Whatever his antecedents, Menshikov had not had a thorough education and while he could read, he never learned to write.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] For the rest of his life, he always wrote through a secretary.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] Menshikov took an active part in the Azov campaigns (1695–1696) against the Ottoman Empire.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] Then, from 1697 to 1698 he accompanied Peter the Great on the Grand Embassy tour of Europe.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] During the Tsar's first foreign tour in the next year, Menshikov worked by his side in the dockyard of Amsterdam, and acquired a thorough knowledge of shipbuilding and colloquial Dutch and German.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] As a result of his dutch shipbuilding education, in 1698, the East India Company issued to Menshikov a shipbuilder's certificate.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] In 1698, on his return to Russia, Menshikov was one of those required to lead the punishment of those *streltsy* soldiers captured during the *streltsy* uprising.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] During the subsequent executions, he later boasted of having cut off twenty heads.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] On the death of Lefort in 1699, Menshikov succeeded him as one of Peter's prime favourites and confidants.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] Menshikov accompanied the Russian forces of the Tsar to besiege the fortress of Nöteborg (renamed *Shlisselburg* by the Russians), then held by the Swedish forces of Charles XII of Sweden in 1702.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] In October, Russian forces succeeding in taking the fortress after the Swedish surrendered following a ten day bombardment.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] As a reward for his service under the Tsar and Marshall Boris Sheremetev, he was made the first Russian governor the re-christened fortress.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] In May 1703, Menshikov participated in the capture of the Swedish fortress of Nyenskans (Nyenschantz), which brought an area of control suitable for the Tsar to establish Saint Petersburg.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] He also accompanied the Tsar in a force of Guards in some 30 boats in a naval action following the seizure in which two Swedish ships were captured.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] As a result of this naval action, Menshikov was awarded the Order of St.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] Later in 1703, following the Russian seizure of land along the Neva and the Gulf of Finland he was appointed the first Governor of the newly established Saint Petersburg.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] It was during this time, that the young Catherine I of Russia had entered Menshikov's household as a servant.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] There are no confirmed accounts that she was Menshikov's mistress, however she later became the mistress of Tsar Peter and rose through the ranks to eventually become the Tsar's wife and later, despite humble origins, Empress in her own right.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] In 1705, he was appointed official governor of the teenage Alexei Petrovich, Tsarevich of Russia.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] Menshikov exercised responsibility for the Tsarevich mostly from afar while on campaign but when meeting in later years, it was said that they did not get on.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] Alexei also claimed that Menshikov had made him a drunkard and tried to poison the Tsarevich.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] In August 1706, he married Darya Mikhailovna, one of his household, who was a companion of Catherine.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] By October 1706, Menshikov commanded forces of the Tsar at the Battle of Kalisz.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] As a reward, the Tsar gave him the Russian title Prince of Izhora, along with large estates.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] In 1706, at the Tsar's request, he was also made a Prince of the Holy Roman Empire.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] Around 1706 he had a conflict with Andrew Vinius; Vinius lost all of his land and goods to Menshikov as he rose in power.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] He acted as subordinate to Boris Sheremetev and Georg Benedikt von Ogilvy during the campaigns before Charles XII in 1708.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] He commanded the cavalry at the Battle of Grodno and during the subsequent retreat.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] He subsequently participated in the battle of Holowczyn in July 1708.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] Following a series of defensive river manoeuvres, Menshikov accompanied the Tsar to intercept the Swedish army of Adam Ludwig Lewenhaupt which resulted in a Russian victory at the Battle of Lesnaya.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] Menshikov commanded the left wing of the Russian army, some eight regiments of Guards and dismounted dragoons.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] Later at the sack of Baturyn in November 1708, Menshikov led Russian forces to sack the capital of the Cossack Hetmanate Ivan Mazepa who had decided to support the Swedish invasion of Russia.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] In January 1709, Menshikov narrowly escaped captured at Opishnia after Charles XII himself led five cavalry regiments to seize control of a river crossing where Menshikov and his forces were resting and having dinner.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] Menshikov led the Russian defences of the region during early 1709, with his headquarters at the village of Krutoy Bereg on the Vorskla river.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] The Tsar arrived in June 1709 to renew offensive actions with Menshikov, resulting in the crowning victory of Poltava (8 July [O.S.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] 27 June] 1709) where Menshikov won his field-marshal's baton.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] At the battle of Poltava, he initially commanded the vanguard of the Russian army, with dragoons at a series of fortified redoubts, before commanding the entire left flank of the Russian forces.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] After the battle, as the surviving Swedish forces retreated, Menshikov and some 6,000 Russian soldiers pursued them over several days.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] This led to the subsequent Surrender at Perevolochna in which Menshikov, who had only a third of the number of soldiers of the Swedish forces opposite him, offered terms to the surviving army under Lewenhaupt.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] As King Charles XII had managed to escape, Lewenhaupt surrendered to Menshikov, resulting in the complete destruction and imprisonment of the remaining Swedish forces outside greater Sweden, which further contributed towards the Russian victory in the Great Northern War.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] From 1709 to 1714 he served during the Courland, Holstein and Pomeranian campaigns, but then, as governor-general of Ingria, with almost unlimited powers, was entrusted with a leading part in the civil administration.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] Menshikov understood perfectly the principles on which Peter's reforms were conducted and was the right hand of the Tsar in all his gigantic undertakings.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] But he abused his powerful position, and his corrupt practices frequently brought him to the verge of ruin, although he survived because Tsar Peter repeatedly forgave his corruption.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] Every time the Tsar returned to Russia he received fresh accusations of plunder against "his Serene Highness." Peter's first serious outburst of indignation (March 1711) was due to the prince's looting in Poland.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] Peter threatened him with execution and Menshikov apologised, which was accepted by the Tsar.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] In an effort to force Charles XII to conclude a formal peace treaty in the years following Poltava, Menshikov led the Russian army in an invasion of Swedish Pomerania in 1711 leading to the so-named Siege of Stralsund.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] This involved the initial ineffective failed siege of the city of Stettin in the Baltic, though Russian forces under Menshikov would succeed in its capture with Saxon army assistance in September 1713.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] On his return to Russia in 1712, Peter discovered that Menshikov had turned a blind eye to wholesale corruption in his own governor-generalship.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] Peter warned him "for the last time" to change his ways.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] By 1713, he was implicated in corruption again in the "Solovey process", in the course of which it was demonstrated that he had defrauded the government of 100,000 roubles.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] He only owed his life on this occasion to a sudden illness.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] On his recovery Peter's fondness for his friend overcame his sense of justice.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] Returning to command Russian forces, his allied coalition succeeded in the Siege of Tönning in May 1713.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] In 1714 he was elected a Fellow of the Royal Society.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] According to Simon Sebag Montefiore in his book *The Romanovs 1613–1918* Menshikov was once punched twice by Tsar Peter the Great, once in the nose and once on the side of the head, after Tsar Peter saw Menshikov dancing with his sword still on, which was considered to rude manners.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] Menshikov was accused of fraud and financial dishonesty along with several other notables in 1715.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] As a result of his rise from humber origins, gathering of huge wealth and favouritism by the Tsar, exaggerated claims were made against Menshikov by some aristrocrats, include Yakov Fyodorovich Dolgorukov.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] An investigation revealed some instances of irregularity but Menshikov was able to moderate the claims and persuade the Tsar that he was acting in the best interests of the state, citing instances of lending money to government and hosting events at his palaces.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] Tsar Peter fined Menshikov but forgave him.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] In 1718, Menshikov was responsible for the arrest of those who helped Alexei Petrovich, Tsarevich of Russia escape Russia before he was forcibly returned.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] The Tsarevich died following torture and Menshikov then swore an oath of allegiance to Peter Petrovich, Tsarevich of Russia as Peter's new heir, however Peter Petrovich died before taking the throne.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] In the last year of Peter's reign new allegations of fraud by Menshikov came to light, and he was obliged to appeal for protection to the empress Catherine.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] Initially sentenced to lose all property and title, Menshikov was again forgiven and restored to all his properties and titles by the Tsar as the Tsar lay ill in his final days.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] It was chiefly through the efforts of Menshikov and his colleague Tolstoi that, on the death of Peter, in 1725, Catherine was raised to the throne.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] Menshikov was committed to the Petrine system, and he recognised that, if that system were to continue, Catherine was, at that particular time, the only possible candidate as a member of the new Russia.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] Her placement on the throne meant a final victory over ancient prejudices, a vindication of the new ideas of progress, and not least security for Menshikov and his ill-gotten fortune.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] During Catherine's short reign (February 1725 – May 1727), Menshikov was practically the de facto absolute ruler of Russia.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] He reduced the influence of the Governing Senate and concentrated power in a new Supreme Privy council.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] He promoted himself to the unprecedented rank of Generalissimo.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] In order to strengthen his and Catherine's position he reduced taxes across Russia by one third for each 'soul'.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] In 1726, he exiled an earlier rival General Anton de Vieira to Siberia.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] De Vieira was his brother law, having married Menshikov's sister despite Menshikov opposing the relationship.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] Following Catherine's death, while his colleague Peter Tolstoi would have raised Elizabeth Petrovna to the throne, Menshikov set up the youthful Peter II, son of Tsarevich Alexei, with himself as dictator during the prince's minority.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] He now aimed at establishing himself definitely by marrying his daughter Maria to Peter II.
[src:siege-of-sevastopol-1854-1855/alexander-danilovich-menshikov] While an engagement was announced, he was soon thwarted by opposition forces.
